<tr>
<td><ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Chorus. </strong><a name='1'></a>Two households, both alike in dignity,
<br>In fair Verona, where we lay our scene,
<br>From ancient grudge break to new mutiny,
<br>Where civil blood makes civil hands unclean.
<br>From forth the fatal loins of these two foes
<span class='playlinenum'>5</span><br>A pair of star-cross'd lovers take their life;
<br>Whose misadventured piteous overthrows
<br>Do with their death bury their parents' strife.
<br>The fearful passage of their death-mark'd love,
<br>And the continuance of their parents' rage,
<span class='playlinenum'>10</span><br>Which, but their children's end, nought could remove,
<br>Is now the two hours' traffic of our stage;
<br>The which if you with patient ears attend,
<br>What here shall miss, our toil shall strive to mend.
</li></ul>


</td>

<p class='stagedir' style='text-align:center'><strong>Verona. A public place.</strong></p>

<table width='600' cellspacing='30'>
<tr>
<td></li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='15'></a>[Enter SAMPSON and GREGORY, of the house of Capulet, armed with swords and bucklers]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Sampson. </strong><a name='16'></a>Gregory, o' my word, we'll not carry coals.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Gregory. </strong><a name='18'></a>No, for then we should be colliers.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Sampson. </strong><a name='19'></a>I mean, an we be in choler, we'll draw.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Gregory. </strong><a name='20'></a>Ay, while you live, draw your neck out o' the collar.
<span class='playlinenum'>20</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Sampson. </strong><a name='21'></a>I strike quickly, being moved.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Gregory. </strong><a name='22'></a>But thou art not quickly moved to strike.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Sampson. </strong><a name='23'></a>A dog of the house of Montague moves me.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Gregory. </strong><a name='24'></a>To move is to stir; and to be valiant is to stand:
<br>therefore, if thou art moved, thou runn'st away.
<span class='playlinenum'>25</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Sampson. </strong><a name='26'></a>A dog of that house shall move me to stand: I will
<br>take the wall of any man or maid of Montague's.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Gregory. </strong><a name='28'></a>That shows thee a weak slave; for the weakest goes
<br>to the wall.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Sampson. </strong><a name='30'></a>True; and therefore women, being the weaker vessels,
<span class='playlinenum'>30</span><br>are ever thrust to the wall: therefore I will push
<br>Montague's men from the wall, and thrust his maids
<br>to the wall.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Gregory. </strong><a name='34'></a>The quarrel is between our masters and us their men.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Sampson. </strong><a name='35'></a>'Tis all one, I will show myself a tyrant: when I
<span class='playlinenum'>35</span><br>have fought with the men, I will be cruel with the
<br>maids, and cut off their heads.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Gregory. </strong><a name='38'></a>The heads of the maids?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Sampson. </strong><a name='39'></a>Ay, the heads of the maids, or their maidenheads;
<br>take it in what sense thou wilt.
<span class='playlinenum'>40</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Gregory. </strong><a name='41'></a>They must take it in sense that feel it.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Sampson. </strong><a name='42'></a>Me they shall feel while I am able to stand: and
<br>'tis known I am a pretty piece of flesh.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Gregory. </strong><a name='44'></a>'Tis well thou art not fish; if thou hadst, thou
<br>hadst been poor John. Draw thy tool! here comes
<span class='playlinenum'>45</span><br>two of the house of the Montagues.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Sampson. </strong><a name='47'></a>My naked weapon is out: quarrel, I will back thee.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Gregory. </strong><a name='48'></a>How! turn thy back and run?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Sampson. </strong><a name='49'></a>Fear me not.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Gregory. </strong><a name='50'></a>No, marry; I fear thee!
<span class='playlinenum'>50</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Sampson. </strong><a name='51'></a>Let us take the law of our sides; let them begin.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Gregory. </strong><a name='52'></a>I will frown as I pass by, and let them take it as
<br>they list.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Sampson. </strong><a name='54'></a>Nay, as they dare. I will bite my thumb at them;
<br>which is a disgrace to them, if they bear it.
<span class='playlinenum'>55</span></li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='56'></a>[Enter ABRAHAM and BALTHASAR]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Abraham. </strong><a name='57'></a>Do you bite your thumb at us, sir?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Sampson. </strong><a name='58'></a>I do bite my thumb, sir.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Abraham. </strong><a name='59'></a>Do you bite your thumb at us, sir?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Sampson. </strong><a name='60'></a><i>[Aside to GREGORY]</i> Is the law of our side, if I say
<span class='playlinenum'>60</span><br>ay?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Gregory. </strong><a name='62'></a>No.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Sampson. </strong><a name='63'></a>No, sir, I do not bite my thumb at you, sir, but I
<br>bite my thumb, sir.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Gregory. </strong><a name='65'></a>Do you quarrel, sir?
<span class='playlinenum'>65</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Abraham. </strong><a name='66'></a>Quarrel sir! no, sir.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Sampson. </strong><a name='67'></a>If you do, sir, I am for you: I serve as good a man as you.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Abraham. </strong><a name='68'></a>No better.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Sampson. </strong><a name='69'></a>Well, sir.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Gregory. </strong><a name='70'></a>Say 'better:' here comes one of my master's kinsmen.
<span class='playlinenum'>70</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Sampson. </strong><a name='71'></a>Yes, better, sir.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Abraham. </strong><a name='72'></a>You lie.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Sampson. </strong><a name='73'></a>Draw, if you be men. Gregory, remember thy swashing blow.
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='74'></a>[They fight]
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='75'></a>[Enter BENVOLIO]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Benvolio. </strong><a name='76'></a>Part, fools!
<br>Put up your swords; you know not what you do.
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='78'></a>[Beats down their swords]
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='79'></a>[Enter TYBALT]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Tybalt. </strong><a name='80'></a>What, art thou drawn among these heartless hinds?
<span class='playlinenum'>80</span><br>Turn thee, Benvolio, look upon thy death.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Benvolio. </strong><a name='82'></a>I do but keep the peace: put up thy sword,
<br>Or manage it to part these men with me.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Tybalt. </strong><a name='84'></a>What, drawn, and talk of peace! I hate the word,
<br>As I hate hell, all Montagues, and thee:
<span class='playlinenum'>85</span><br>Have at thee, coward!
<br><i>[They fight]</i>
<br><i>[Enter, several of both houses, who join the fray;
<br>then enter Citizens, with clubs]</i>
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>First Citizen. </strong><a name='90'></a>Clubs, bills, and partisans! strike! beat them down!
<span class='playlinenum'>90</span><br>Down with the Capulets! down with the Montagues!
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='92'></a>[Enter CAPULET in his gown, and LADY CAPULET]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Capulet. </strong><a name='93'></a>What noise is this? Give me my long sword, ho!
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Lady Capulet. </strong><a name='94'></a>A crutch, a crutch! why call you for a sword?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Capulet. </strong><a name='95'></a>My sword, I say! Old Montague is come,
<span class='playlinenum'>95</span><br>And flourishes his blade in spite of me.
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='97'></a>[Enter MONTAGUE and LADY MONTAGUE]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Montague. </strong><a name='98'></a>Thou villain Capulet,&mdash;Hold me not, let me go.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Lady Montague. </strong><a name='99'></a>Thou shalt not stir a foot to seek a foe.
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='100'></a>[Enter PRINCE, with Attendants]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Prince Escalus. </strong><a name='101'></a>Rebellious subjects, enemies to peace,
<br>Profaners of this neighbour-stained steel,&mdash;
<br>Will they not hear? What, ho! you men, you beasts,
<br>That quench the fire of your pernicious rage
<br>With purple fountains issuing from your veins,
<span class='playlinenum'>105</span><br>On pain of torture, from those bloody hands
<br>Throw your mistemper'd weapons to the ground,
<br>And hear the sentence of your moved prince.
<br>Three civil brawls, bred of an airy word,
<br>By thee, old Capulet, and Montague,
<span class='playlinenum'>110</span><br>Have thrice disturb'd the quiet of our streets,
<br>And made Verona's ancient citizens
<br>Cast by their grave beseeming ornaments,
<br>To wield old partisans, in hands as old,
<br>Canker'd with peace, to part your canker'd hate:
<span class='playlinenum'>115</span><br>If ever you disturb our streets again,
<br>Your lives shall pay the forfeit of the peace.
<br>For this time, all the rest depart away:
<br>You Capulet; shall go along with me:
<br>And, Montague, come you this afternoon,
<span class='playlinenum'>120</span><br>To know our further pleasure in this case,
<br>To old Free-town, our common judgment-place.
<br>Once more, on pain of death, all men depart.
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='124'></a>[Exeunt all but MONTAGUE, LADY MONTAGUE, and BENVOLIO]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Montague. </strong><a name='125'></a>Who set this ancient quarrel new abroach?
<span class='playlinenum'>125</span><br>Speak, nephew, were you by when it began?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Benvolio. </strong><a name='127'></a>Here were the servants of your adversary,
<br>And yours, close fighting ere I did approach:
<br>I drew to part them: in the instant came
<br>The fiery Tybalt, with his sword prepared,
<span class='playlinenum'>130</span><br>Which, as he breathed defiance to my ears,
<br>He swung about his head and cut the winds,
<br>Who nothing hurt withal hiss'd him in scorn:
<br>While we were interchanging thrusts and blows,
<br>Came more and more and fought on part and part,
<span class='playlinenum'>135</span><br>Till the prince came, who parted either part.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Lady Montague. </strong><a name='137'></a>O, where is Romeo? saw you him to-day?
<br>Right glad I am he was not at this fray.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Benvolio. </strong><a name='139'></a>Madam, an hour before the worshipp'd sun
<br>Peer'd forth the golden window of the east,
<span class='playlinenum'>140</span><br>A troubled mind drave me to walk abroad;
<br>Where, underneath the grove of sycamore
<br>That westward rooteth from the city's side,
<br>So early walking did I see your son:
<br>Towards him I made, but he was ware of me
<span class='playlinenum'>145</span><br>And stole into the covert of the wood:
<br>I, measuring his affections by my own,
<br>That most are busied when they're most alone,
<br>Pursued my humour not pursuing his,
<br>And gladly shunn'd who gladly fled from me.
<span class='playlinenum'>150</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Montague. </strong><a name='151'></a>Many a morning hath he there been seen,
<br>With tears augmenting the fresh morning dew.
<br>Adding to clouds more clouds with his deep sighs;
<br>But all so soon as the all-cheering sun
<br>Should in the furthest east begin to draw
<span class='playlinenum'>155</span><br>The shady curtains from Aurora's bed,
<br>Away from the light steals home my heavy son,
<br>And private in his chamber pens himself,
<br>Shuts up his windows, locks far daylight out
<br>And makes himself an artificial night:
<span class='playlinenum'>160</span><br>Black and portentous must this humour prove,
<br>Unless good counsel may the cause remove.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Benvolio. </strong><a name='163'></a>My noble uncle, do you know the cause?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Montague. </strong><a name='164'></a>I neither know it nor can learn of him.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Benvolio. </strong><a name='165'></a>Have you importuned him by any means?
<span class='playlinenum'>165</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Montague. </strong><a name='166'></a>Both by myself and many other friends:
<br>But he, his own affections' counsellor,
<br>Is to himself&mdash;I will not say how true&mdash;
<br>But to himself so secret and so close,
<br>So far from sounding and discovery,
<span class='playlinenum'>170</span><br>As is the bud bit with an envious worm,
<br>Ere he can spread his sweet leaves to the air,
<br>Or dedicate his beauty to the sun.
<br>Could we but learn from whence his sorrows grow.
<br>We would as willingly give cure as know.
<span class='playlinenum'>175</span></li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='176'></a>[Enter ROMEO]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Benvolio. </strong><a name='177'></a>See, where he comes: so please you, step aside;
<br>I'll know his grievance, or be much denied.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Montague. </strong><a name='179'></a>I would thou wert so happy by thy stay,
<br>To hear true shrift. Come, madam, let's away.
<span class='playlinenum'>180</span></li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='181'></a>[Exeunt MONTAGUE and LADY MONTAGUE]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Benvolio. </strong><a name='182'></a>Good-morrow, cousin.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='183'></a>Is the day so young?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Benvolio. </strong><a name='184'></a>But new struck nine.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='185'></a>Ay me! sad hours seem long.
<span class='playlinenum'>185</span><br>Was that my father that went hence so fast?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Benvolio. </strong><a name='187'></a>It was. What sadness lengthens Romeo's hours?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='188'></a>Not having that, which, having, makes them short.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Benvolio. </strong><a name='189'></a>In love?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='190'></a>Out&mdash;
<span class='playlinenum'>190</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Benvolio. </strong><a name='191'></a>Of love?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='192'></a>Out of her favour, where I am in love.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Benvolio. </strong><a name='193'></a>Alas, that love, so gentle in his view,
<br>Should be so tyrannous and rough in proof!
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='195'></a>Alas, that love, whose view is muffled still,
<span class='playlinenum'>195</span><br>Should, without eyes, see pathways to his will!
<br>Where shall we dine? O me! What fray was here?
<br>Yet tell me not, for I have heard it all.
<br>Here's much to do with hate, but more with love.
<br>Why, then, O brawling love! O loving hate!
<span class='playlinenum'>200</span><br>O any thing, of nothing first create!
<br>O heavy lightness! serious vanity!
<br>Mis-shapen chaos of well-seeming forms!
<br>Feather of lead, bright smoke, cold fire,
<br>sick health!
<span class='playlinenum'>205</span><br>Still-waking sleep, that is not what it is!
<br>This love feel I, that feel no love in this.
<br>Dost thou not laugh?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Benvolio. </strong><a name='209'></a>No, coz, I rather weep.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='210'></a>Good heart, at what?
<span class='playlinenum'>210</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Benvolio. </strong><a name='211'></a>At thy good heart's oppression.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='212'></a>Why, such is love's transgression.
<br>Griefs of mine own lie heavy in my breast,
<br>Which thou wilt propagate, to have it prest
<br>With more of thine: this love that thou hast shown
<span class='playlinenum'>215</span><br>Doth add more grief to too much of mine own.
<br>Love is a smoke raised with the fume of sighs;
<br>Being purged, a fire sparkling in lovers' eyes;
<br>Being vex'd a sea nourish'd with lovers' tears:
<br>What is it else? a madness most discreet,
<span class='playlinenum'>220</span><br>A choking gall and a preserving sweet.
<br>Farewell, my coz.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Benvolio. </strong><a name='223'></a>Soft! I will go along;
<br>An if you leave me so, you do me wrong.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='225'></a>Tut, I have lost myself; I am not here;
<span class='playlinenum'>225</span><br>This is not Romeo, he's some other where.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Benvolio. </strong><a name='227'></a>Tell me in sadness, who is that you love.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='228'></a>What, shall I groan and tell thee?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Benvolio. </strong><a name='229'></a>Groan! why, no.
<br>But sadly tell me who.
<span class='playlinenum'>230</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='231'></a>Bid a sick man in sadness make his will:
<br>Ah, word ill urged to one that is so ill!
<br>In sadness, cousin, I do love a woman.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Benvolio. </strong><a name='234'></a>I aim'd so near, when I supposed you loved.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='235'></a>A right good mark-man! And she's fair I love.
<span class='playlinenum'>235</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Benvolio. </strong><a name='236'></a>A right fair mark, fair coz, is soonest hit.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='237'></a>Well, in that hit you miss: she'll not be hit
<br>With Cupid's arrow; she hath Dian's wit;
<br>And, in strong proof of chastity well arm'd,
<br>From love's weak childish bow she lives unharm'd.
<span class='playlinenum'>240</span><br>She will not stay the siege of loving terms,
<br>Nor bide the encounter of assailing eyes,
<br>Nor ope her lap to saint-seducing gold:
<br>O, she is rich in beauty, only poor,
<br>That when she dies with beauty dies her store.
<span class='playlinenum'>245</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Benvolio. </strong><a name='246'></a>Then she hath sworn that she will still live chaste?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='247'></a>She hath, and in that sparing makes huge waste,
<br>For beauty starved with her severity
<br>Cuts beauty off from all posterity.
<br>She is too fair, too wise, wisely too fair,
<span class='playlinenum'>250</span><br>To merit bliss by making me despair:
<br>She hath forsworn to love, and in that vow
<br>Do I live dead that live to tell it now.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Benvolio. </strong><a name='254'></a>Be ruled by me, forget to think of her.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='255'></a>O, teach me how I should forget to think.
<span class='playlinenum'>255</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Benvolio. </strong><a name='256'></a>By giving liberty unto thine eyes;
<br>Examine other beauties.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='258'></a>'Tis the way
<br>To call hers exquisite, in question more:
<br>These happy masks that kiss fair ladies' brows
<span class='playlinenum'>260</span><br>Being black put us in mind they hide the fair;
<br>He that is strucken blind cannot forget
<br>The precious treasure of his eyesight lost:
<br>Show me a mistress that is passing fair,
<br>What doth her beauty serve, but as a note
<span class='playlinenum'>265</span><br>Where I may read who pass'd that passing fair?
<br>Farewell: thou canst not teach me to forget.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Benvolio. </strong><a name='268'></a>I'll pay that doctrine, or else die in debt.
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='269'></a>[Exeunt]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Capulet. </strong><a name='271'></a>But Montague is bound as well as I,
<br>In penalty alike; and 'tis not hard, I think,
<br>For men so old as we to keep the peace.

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Paris. </strong><a name='274'></a>Of honourable reckoning are you both;
<br>And pity 'tis you lived at odds so long.
<span class='playlinenum'>275</span><br>But now, my lord, what say you to my suit?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Capulet. </strong><a name='277'></a>But saying o'er what I have said before:
<br>My child is yet a stranger in the world;
<br>She hath not seen the change of fourteen years,
<br>Let two more summers wither in their pride,
<span class='playlinenum'>280</span><br>Ere we may think her ripe to be a bride.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Paris. </strong><a name='282'></a>Younger than she are happy mothers made.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Capulet. </strong><a name='283'></a>And too soon marr'd are those so early made.
<br>The earth hath swallow'd all my hopes but she,
<br>She is the hopeful lady of my earth:
<span class='playlinenum'>285</span><br>But woo her, gentle Paris, get her heart,
<br>My will to her consent is but a part;
<br>An she agree, within her scope of choice
<br>Lies my consent and fair according voice.
<br>This night I hold an old accustom'd feast,
<span class='playlinenum'>290</span><br>Whereto I have invited many a guest,
<br>Such as I love; and you, among the store,
<br>One more, most welcome, makes my number more.
<br>At my poor house look to behold this night
<br>Earth-treading stars that make dark heaven light:
<span class='playlinenum'>295</span><br>Such comfort as do lusty young men feel
<br>When well-apparell'd April on the heel
<br>Of limping winter treads, even such delight
<br>Among fresh female buds shall you this night
<br>Inherit at my house; hear all, all see,
<span class='playlinenum'>300</span><br>And like her most whose merit most shall be:
<br>Which on more view, of many mine being one
<br>May stand in number, though in reckoning none,
<br>Come, go with me.
<br><i>[To Servant, giving a paper]</i>
<span class='playlinenum'>305</span><br>Go, sirrah, trudge about
<br>Through fair Verona; find those persons out
<br>Whose names are written there, and to them say,
<br>My house and welcome on their pleasure stay.

<br>sent to find those persons whose names are here
<span class='playlinenum'>315</span><br>writ, and can never find what names the writing
<br>person hath here writ. I must to the learned.&mdash;In good time.

</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Benvolio. </strong><a name='328'></a>Why, Romeo, art thou mad?
</li></ul>

<span class='playlinenum'>330</span><br>Whipp'd and tormented and&mdash;God-den, good fellow.

</li></ul>

<span class='playlinenum'>335</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='336'></a>Ay, if I know the letters and the language.

<span class='playlinenum'>340</span><br>County Anselme and his beauteous sisters; the lady

</li></ul>

</li></ul>

<span class='playlinenum'>350</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='351'></a>Whose house?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Servant. </strong><a name='352'></a>My master's.
</li></ul>

<td></li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='380'></a>[Enter LADY CAPULET and Nurse]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Lady Capulet. </strong><a name='381'></a>Nurse, where's my daughter? call her forth to me.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Nurse. </strong><a name='382'></a>Now, by my maidenhead, at twelve year old,
<br>I bade her come. What, lamb! what, ladybird!
<br>God forbid! Where's this girl? What, Juliet!
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='385'></a>[Enter JULIET]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='386'></a>How now! who calls?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Nurse. </strong><a name='387'></a>Your mother.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='388'></a>Madam, I am here.
<br>What is your will?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Lady Capulet. </strong><a name='390'></a>This is the matter:&mdash;Nurse, give leave awhile,
<span class='playlinenum'>390</span><br>We must talk in secret:&mdash;nurse, come back again;
<br>I have remember'd me, thou's hear our counsel.
<br>Thou know'st my daughter's of a pretty age.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Nurse. </strong><a name='394'></a>Faith, I can tell her age unto an hour.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Lady Capulet. </strong><a name='395'></a>She's not fourteen.
<span class='playlinenum'>395</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Nurse. </strong><a name='396'></a>I'll lay fourteen of my teeth,&mdash;
<br>And yet, to my teeth be it spoken, I have but four&mdash;
<br>She is not fourteen. How long is it now
<br>To Lammas-tide?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Lady Capulet. </strong><a name='400'></a>A fortnight and odd days.
<span class='playlinenum'>400</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Nurse. </strong><a name='401'></a>Even or odd, of all days in the year,
<br>Come Lammas-eve at night shall she be fourteen.
<br>Susan and she&mdash;God rest all Christian souls!&mdash;
<br>Were of an age: well, Susan is with God;
<br>She was too good for me: but, as I said,
<span class='playlinenum'>405</span><br>On Lammas-eve at night shall she be fourteen;
<br>That shall she, marry; I remember it well.
<br>'Tis since the earthquake now eleven years;
<br>And she was wean'd,&mdash;I never shall forget it,&mdash;
<br>Of all the days of the year, upon that day:
<span class='playlinenum'>410</span><br>For I had then laid wormwood to my dug,
<br>Sitting in the sun under the dove-house wall;
<br>My lord and you were then at Mantua:&mdash;
<br>Nay, I do bear a brain:&mdash;but, as I said,
<br>When it did taste the wormwood on the nipple
<span class='playlinenum'>415</span><br>Of my dug and felt it bitter, pretty fool,
<br>To see it tetchy and fall out with the dug!
<br>Shake quoth the dove-house: 'twas no need, I trow,
<br>To bid me trudge:
<br>And since that time it is eleven years;
<span class='playlinenum'>420</span><br>For then she could stand alone; nay, by the rood,
<br>She could have run and waddled all about;
<br>For even the day before, she broke her brow:
<br>And then my husband&mdash;God be with his soul!
<br>A' was a merry man&mdash;took up the child:
<span class='playlinenum'>425</span><br>'Yea,' quoth he, 'dost thou fall upon thy face?
<br>Thou wilt fall backward when thou hast more wit;
<br>Wilt thou not, Jule?' and, by my holidame,
<br>The pretty wretch left crying and said 'Ay.'
<br>To see, now, how a jest shall come about!
<span class='playlinenum'>430</span><br>I warrant, an I should live a thousand years,
<br>I never should forget it: 'Wilt thou not, Jule?' quoth he;
<br>And, pretty fool, it stinted and said 'Ay.'
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Lady Capulet. </strong><a name='434'></a>Enough of this; I pray thee, hold thy peace.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Nurse. </strong><a name='435'></a>Yes, madam: yet I cannot choose but laugh,
<span class='playlinenum'>435</span><br>To think it should leave crying and say 'Ay.'
<br>And yet, I warrant, it had upon its brow
<br>A bump as big as a young cockerel's stone;
<br>A parlous knock; and it cried bitterly:
<br>'Yea,' quoth my husband,'fall'st upon thy face?
<span class='playlinenum'>440</span><br>Thou wilt fall backward when thou comest to age;
<br>Wilt thou not, Jule?' it stinted and said 'Ay.'
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='443'></a>And stint thou too, I pray thee, nurse, say I.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Nurse. </strong><a name='444'></a>Peace, I have done. God mark thee to his grace!
<br>Thou wast the prettiest babe that e'er I nursed:
<span class='playlinenum'>445</span><br>An I might live to see thee married once,
<br>I have my wish.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Lady Capulet. </strong><a name='448'></a>Marry, that 'marry' is the very theme
<br>I came to talk of. Tell me, daughter Juliet,
<br>How stands your disposition to be married?
<span class='playlinenum'>450</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='451'></a>It is an honour that I dream not of.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Nurse. </strong><a name='452'></a>An honour! were not I thine only nurse,
<br>I would say thou hadst suck'd wisdom from thy teat.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Lady Capulet. </strong><a name='454'></a>Well, think of marriage now; younger than you,
<br>Here in Verona, ladies of esteem,
<span class='playlinenum'>455</span><br>Are made already mothers: by my count,
<br>I was your mother much upon these years
<br>That you are now a maid. Thus then in brief:
<br>The valiant Paris seeks you for his love.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Nurse. </strong><a name='460'></a>A man, young lady! lady, such a man
<span class='playlinenum'>460</span><br>As all the world&mdash;why, he's a man of wax.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Lady Capulet. </strong><a name='462'></a>Verona's summer hath not such a flower.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Nurse. </strong><a name='463'></a>Nay, he's a flower; in faith, a very flower.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Lady Capulet. </strong><a name='464'></a>What say you? can you love the gentleman?
<br>This night you shall behold him at our feast;
<span class='playlinenum'>465</span><br>Read o'er the volume of young Paris' face,
<br>And find delight writ there with beauty's pen;
<br>Examine every married lineament,
<br>And see how one another lends content
<br>And what obscured in this fair volume lies
<span class='playlinenum'>470</span><br>Find written in the margent of his eyes.
<br>This precious book of love, this unbound lover,
<br>To beautify him, only lacks a cover:
<br>The fish lives in the sea, and 'tis much pride
<br>For fair without the fair within to hide:
<span class='playlinenum'>475</span><br>That book in many's eyes doth share the glory,
<br>That in gold clasps locks in the golden story;
<br>So shall you share all that he doth possess,
<br>By having him, making yourself no less.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Nurse. </strong><a name='480'></a>No less! nay, bigger; women grow by men.
<span class='playlinenum'>480</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Lady Capulet. </strong><a name='481'></a>Speak briefly, can you like of Paris' love?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='482'></a>I'll look to like, if looking liking move:
<br>But no more deep will I endart mine eye
<br>Than your consent gives strength to make it fly.
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='485'></a>[Enter a Servant]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Servant. </strong><a name='486'></a>Madam, the guests are come, supper served up, you
<br>called, my young lady asked for, the nurse cursed in
<br>the pantry, and every thing in extremity. I must
<br>hence to wait; I beseech you, follow straight.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Lady Capulet. </strong><a name='490'></a>We follow thee.
<span class='playlinenum'>490</span><br><i>[Exit Servant]</i>
<br>Juliet, the county stays.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Nurse. </strong><a name='493'></a>Go, girl, seek happy nights to happy days.
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='494'></a>[Exeunt]
</li></ul>

<td></li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='495'></a>[Enter ROMEO, MERCUTIO, BENVOLIO, with five or six
[p]Maskers, Torch-bearers, and others]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='497'></a>What, shall this speech be spoke for our excuse?
<br>Or shall we on without a apology?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Benvolio. </strong><a name='499'></a>The date is out of such prolixity:
<br>We'll have no Cupid hoodwink'd with a scarf,
<span class='playlinenum'>500</span><br>Bearing a Tartar's painted bow of lath,
<br>Scaring the ladies like a crow-keeper;
<br>Nor no without-book prologue, faintly spoke
<br>After the prompter, for our entrance:
<br>But let them measure us by what they will;
<span class='playlinenum'>505</span><br>We'll measure them a measure, and be gone.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='507'></a>Give me a torch: I am not for this ambling;
<br>Being but heavy, I will bear the light.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Mercutio. </strong><a name='509'></a>Nay, gentle Romeo, we must have you dance.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='510'></a>Not I, believe me: you have dancing shoes
<span class='playlinenum'>510</span><br>With nimble soles: I have a soul of lead
<br>So stakes me to the ground I cannot move.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Mercutio. </strong><a name='513'></a>You are a lover; borrow Cupid's wings,
<br>And soar with them above a common bound.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='515'></a>I am too sore enpierced with his shaft
<span class='playlinenum'>515</span><br>To soar with his light feathers, and so bound,
<br>I cannot bound a pitch above dull woe:
<br>Under love's heavy burden do I sink.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Mercutio. </strong><a name='519'></a>And, to sink in it, should you burden love;
<br>Too great oppression for a tender thing.
<span class='playlinenum'>520</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='521'></a>Is love a tender thing? it is too rough,
<br>Too rude, too boisterous, and it pricks like thorn.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Mercutio. </strong><a name='523'></a>If love be rough with you, be rough with love;
<br>Prick love for pricking, and you beat love down.
<br>Give me a case to put my visage in:
<span class='playlinenum'>525</span><br>A visor for a visor! what care I
<br>What curious eye doth quote deformities?
<br>Here are the beetle brows shall blush for me.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Benvolio. </strong><a name='529'></a>Come, knock and enter; and no sooner in,
<br>But every man betake him to his legs.
<span class='playlinenum'>530</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='531'></a>A torch for me: let wantons light of heart
<br>Tickle the senseless rushes with their heels,
<br>For I am proverb'd with a grandsire phrase;
<br>I'll be a candle-holder, and look on.
<br>The game was ne'er so fair, and I am done.
<span class='playlinenum'>535</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Mercutio. </strong><a name='536'></a>Tut, dun's the mouse, the constable's own word:
<br>If thou art dun, we'll draw thee from the mire
<br>Of this sir-reverence love, wherein thou stick'st
<br>Up to the ears. Come, we burn daylight, ho!
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='540'></a>Nay, that's not so.
<span class='playlinenum'>540</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Mercutio. </strong><a name='541'></a>I mean, sir, in delay
<br>We waste our lights in vain, like lamps by day.
<br>Take our good meaning, for our judgment sits
<br>Five times in that ere once in our five wits.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='545'></a>And we mean well in going to this mask;
<span class='playlinenum'>545</span><br>But 'tis no wit to go.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Mercutio. </strong><a name='547'></a>Why, may one ask?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='548'></a>I dream'd a dream to-night.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Mercutio. </strong><a name='549'></a>And so did I.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='550'></a>Well, what was yours?
<span class='playlinenum'>550</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Mercutio. </strong><a name='551'></a>That dreamers often lie.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='552'></a>In bed asleep, while they do dream things true.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Mercutio. </strong><a name='553'></a>O, then, I see Queen Mab hath been with you.
<br>She is the fairies' midwife, and she comes
<br>In shape no bigger than an agate-stone
<span class='playlinenum'>555</span><br>On the fore-finger of an alderman,
<br>Drawn with a team of little atomies
<br>Athwart men's noses as they lie asleep;
<br>Her wagon-spokes made of long spiders' legs,
<br>The cover of the wings of grasshoppers,
<span class='playlinenum'>560</span><br>The traces of the smallest spider's web,
<br>The collars of the moonshine's watery beams,
<br>Her whip of cricket's bone, the lash of film,
<br>Her wagoner a small grey-coated gnat,
<br>Not so big as a round little worm
<span class='playlinenum'>565</span><br>Prick'd from the lazy finger of a maid;
<br>Her chariot is an empty hazel-nut
<br>Made by the joiner squirrel or old grub,
<br>Time out o' mind the fairies' coachmakers.
<br>And in this state she gallops night by night
<span class='playlinenum'>570</span><br>Through lovers' brains, and then they dream of love;
<br>O'er courtiers' knees, that dream on court'sies straight,
<br>O'er lawyers' fingers, who straight dream on fees,
<br>O'er ladies ' lips, who straight on kisses dream,
<br>Which oft the angry Mab with blisters plagues,
<span class='playlinenum'>575</span><br>Because their breaths with sweetmeats tainted are:
<br>Sometime she gallops o'er a courtier's nose,
<br>And then dreams he of smelling out a suit;
<br>And sometime comes she with a tithe-pig's tail
<br>Tickling a parson's nose as a' lies asleep,
<span class='playlinenum'>580</span><br>Then dreams, he of another benefice:
<br>Sometime she driveth o'er a soldier's neck,
<br>And then dreams he of cutting foreign throats,
<br>Of breaches, ambuscadoes, Spanish blades,
<br>Of healths five-fathom deep; and then anon
<span class='playlinenum'>585</span><br>Drums in his ear, at which he starts and wakes,
<br>And being thus frighted swears a prayer or two
<br>And sleeps again. This is that very Mab
<br>That plats the manes of horses in the night,
<br>And bakes the elflocks in foul sluttish hairs,
<span class='playlinenum'>590</span><br>Which once untangled, much misfortune bodes:
<br>This is the hag, when maids lie on their backs,
<br>That presses them and learns them first to bear,
<br>Making them women of good carriage:
<br>This is she&mdash;
<span class='playlinenum'>595</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='596'></a>Peace, peace, Mercutio, peace!
<br>Thou talk'st of nothing.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Mercutio. </strong><a name='598'></a>True, I talk of dreams,
<br>Which are the children of an idle brain,
<br>Begot of nothing but vain fantasy,
<span class='playlinenum'>600</span><br>Which is as thin of substance as the air
<br>And more inconstant than the wind, who wooes
<br>Even now the frozen bosom of the north,
<br>And, being anger'd, puffs away from thence,
<br>Turning his face to the dew-dropping south.
<span class='playlinenum'>605</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Benvolio. </strong><a name='606'></a>This wind, you talk of, blows us from ourselves;
<br>Supper is done, and we shall come too late.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='608'></a>I fear, too early: for my mind misgives
<br>Some consequence yet hanging in the stars
<br>Shall bitterly begin his fearful date
<span class='playlinenum'>610</span><br>With this night's revels and expire the term
<br>Of a despised life closed in my breast
<br>By some vile forfeit of untimely death.
<br>But He, that hath the steerage of my course,
<br>Direct my sail! On, lusty gentlemen.
<span class='playlinenum'>615</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Benvolio. </strong><a name='616'></a>Strike, drum.
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='617'></a>[Exeunt]
</li></ul>

<span class='playlinenum'>665</span></li></ul>

<br>So shows a snowy dove trooping with crows,
<span class='playlinenum'>670</span><br>As yonder lady o'er her fellows shows.
<br>The measure done, I'll watch her place of stand,
<br>And, touching hers, make blessed my rude hand.

<span class='playlinenum'>675</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Tybalt. </strong><a name='676'></a>This, by his voice, should be a Montague.

<span class='playlinenum'>680</span><br>To strike him dead, I hold it not a sin.

</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Tybalt. </strong><a name='683'></a>Uncle, this is a Montague, our foe,

<br>To scorn at our solemnity this night.
<span class='playlinenum'>685</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Capulet. </strong><a name='686'></a>Young Romeo is it?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Tybalt. </strong><a name='687'></a>'Tis he, that villain Romeo.
</li></ul>

<br>He bears him like a portly gentleman;
<br>And, to say truth, Verona brags of him
<span class='playlinenum'>690</span><br>To be a virtuous and well-govern'd youth:
<br>I would not for the wealth of all the town
<br>Here in my house do him disparagement:
<br>Therefore be patient, take no note of him:
<br>It is my will, the which if thou respect,
<span class='playlinenum'>695</span><br>Show a fair presence and put off these frowns,
<br>And ill-beseeming semblance for a feast.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Tybalt. </strong><a name='698'></a>It fits, when such a villain is a guest:

</li></ul>

<span class='playlinenum'>700</span><br>What, goodman boy! I say, he shall: go to;

<br>You'll not endure him! God shall mend my soul!

<br>You will set cock-a-hoop! you'll be the man!
<span class='playlinenum'>705</span></li></ul>

<span class='playlinenum'>710</span><br>Well said, my hearts! You are a princox; go:

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='723'></a>Good pilgrim, you do wrong your hand too much,

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='729'></a>O, then, dear saint, let lips do what hands do;
<br>They pray, grant thou, lest faith turn to despair.
<span class='playlinenum'>730</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='731'></a>Saints do not move, though grant for prayers' sake.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='732'></a>Then move not, while my prayer's effect I take.
<br>Thus from my lips, by yours, my sin is purged.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='734'></a>Then have my lips the sin that they have took.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='735'></a>Sin from thy lips? O trespass sweetly urged!
<span class='playlinenum'>735</span><br>Give me my sin again.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='737'></a>You kiss by the book.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Nurse. </strong><a name='738'></a>Madam, your mother craves a word with you.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='739'></a>What is her mother?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Nurse. </strong><a name='740'></a>Marry, bachelor,
<span class='playlinenum'>740</span><br>Her mother is the lady of the house,
<br>And a good lady, and a wise and virtuous
<br>I nursed her daughter, that you talk'd withal;
<br>I tell you, he that can lay hold of her
<br>Shall have the chinks.
<span class='playlinenum'>745</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='746'></a>Is she a Capulet?
<br>O dear account! my life is my foe's debt.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Benvolio. </strong><a name='748'></a>Away, begone; the sport is at the best.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='749'></a>Ay, so I fear; the more is my unrest.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Capulet. </strong><a name='750'></a>Nay, gentlemen, prepare not to be gone;
<span class='playlinenum'>750</span><br>We have a trifling foolish banquet towards.
<br>Is it e'en so? why, then, I thank you all
<br>I thank you, honest gentlemen; good night.
<br>More torches here! Come on then, let's to bed.
<br>Ah, sirrah, by my fay, it waxes late:
<span class='playlinenum'>755</span><br>I'll to my rest.
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='757'></a>[Exeunt all but JULIET and Nurse]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='758'></a>Come hither, nurse. What is yond gentleman?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Nurse. </strong><a name='759'></a>The son and heir of old Tiberio.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='760'></a>What's he that now is going out of door?
<span class='playlinenum'>760</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Nurse. </strong><a name='761'></a>Marry, that, I think, be young Petrucio.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='762'></a>What's he that follows there, that would not dance?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Nurse. </strong><a name='763'></a>I know not.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='764'></a>Go ask his name: if he be married.
<br>My grave is like to be my wedding bed.
<span class='playlinenum'>765</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Nurse. </strong><a name='766'></a>His name is Romeo, and a Montague;
<br>The only son of your great enemy.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='768'></a>My only love sprung from my only hate!
<br>Too early seen unknown, and known too late!
<br>Prodigious birth of love it is to me,
<span class='playlinenum'>770</span><br>That I must love a loathed enemy.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Nurse. </strong><a name='772'></a>What's this? what's this?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='773'></a>A rhyme I learn'd even now
<br>Of one I danced withal.
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='775'></a>[One calls within 'Juliet.']
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Nurse. </strong><a name='776'></a>Anon, anon!
<br>Come, let's away; the strangers all are gone.
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='778'></a>[Exeunt]
</li></ul>

<td></li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='844'></a>[Enter ROMEO]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='845'></a>He jests at scars that never felt a wound.
<span class='playlinenum'>845</span><br><i>[JULIET appears above at a window]</i>
<br>But, soft! what light through yonder window breaks?
<br>It is the east, and Juliet is the sun.
<br>Arise, fair sun, and kill the envious moon,
<br>Who is already sick and pale with grief,
<span class='playlinenum'>850</span><br>That thou her maid art far more fair than she:
<br>Be not her maid, since she is envious;
<br>Her vestal livery is but sick and green
<br>And none but fools do wear it; cast it off.
<br>It is my lady, O, it is my love!
<span class='playlinenum'>855</span><br>O, that she knew she were!
<br>She speaks yet she says nothing: what of that?
<br>Her eye discourses; I will answer it.
<br>I am too bold, 'tis not to me she speaks:
<br>Two of the fairest stars in all the heaven,
<span class='playlinenum'>860</span><br>Having some business, do entreat her eyes
<br>To twinkle in their spheres till they return.
<br>What if her eyes were there, they in her head?
<br>The brightness of her cheek would shame those stars,
<br>As daylight doth a lamp; her eyes in heaven
<span class='playlinenum'>865</span><br>Would through the airy region stream so bright
<br>That birds would sing and think it were not night.
<br>See, how she leans her cheek upon her hand!
<br>O, that I were a glove upon that hand,
<br>That I might touch that cheek!
<span class='playlinenum'>870</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='871'></a>Ay me!
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='872'></a>She speaks:
<br>O, speak again, bright angel! for thou art
<br>As glorious to this night, being o'er my head
<br>As is a winged messenger of heaven
<span class='playlinenum'>875</span><br>Unto the white-upturned wondering eyes
<br>Of mortals that fall back to gaze on him
<br>When he bestrides the lazy-pacing clouds
<br>And sails upon the bosom of the air.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='880'></a>O Romeo, Romeo! wherefore art thou Romeo?
<span class='playlinenum'>880</span><br>Deny thy father and refuse thy name;
<br>Or, if thou wilt not, be but sworn my love,
<br>And I'll no longer be a Capulet.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='884'></a><i>[Aside]</i> Shall I hear more, or shall I speak at this?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='885'></a>'Tis but thy name that is my enemy;
<span class='playlinenum'>885</span><br>Thou art thyself, though not a Montague.
<br>What's Montague? it is nor hand, nor foot,
<br>Nor arm, nor face, nor any other part
<br>Belonging to a man. O, be some other name!
<br>What's in a name? that which we call a rose
<span class='playlinenum'>890</span><br>By any other name would smell as sweet;
<br>So Romeo would, were he not Romeo call'd,
<br>Retain that dear perfection which he owes
<br>Without that title. Romeo, doff thy name,
<br>And for that name which is no part of thee
<span class='playlinenum'>895</span><br>Take all myself.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='897'></a>I take thee at thy word:
<br>Call me but love, and I'll be new baptized;
<br>Henceforth I never will be Romeo.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='900'></a>What man art thou that thus bescreen'd in night
<span class='playlinenum'>900</span><br>So stumblest on my counsel?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='902'></a>By a name
<br>I know not how to tell thee who I am:
<br>My name, dear saint, is hateful to myself,
<br>Because it is an enemy to thee;
<span class='playlinenum'>905</span><br>Had I it written, I would tear the word.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='907'></a>My ears have not yet drunk a hundred words
<br>Of that tongue's utterance, yet I know the sound:
<br>Art thou not Romeo and a Montague?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='910'></a>Neither, fair saint, if either thee dislike.
<span class='playlinenum'>910</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='911'></a>How camest thou hither, tell me, and wherefore?

<br>If any of my kinsmen find thee here.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='915'></a>With love's light wings did I o'er-perch these walls;
<span class='playlinenum'>915</span><br>For stony limits cannot hold love out,
<br>And what love can do that dares love attempt;
<br>Therefore thy kinsmen are no let to me.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='919'></a>If they do see thee, they will murder thee.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='920'></a>Alack, there lies more peril in thine eye
<span class='playlinenum'>920</span><br>Than twenty of their swords: look thou but sweet,
<br>And I am proof against their enmity.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='923'></a>I would not for the world they saw thee here.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='924'></a>I have night's cloak to hide me from their sight;

<span class='playlinenum'>925</span><br>My life were better ended by their hate,
<br>Than death prorogued, wanting of thy love.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='928'></a>By whose direction found'st thou out this place?

<span class='playlinenum'>930</span><br>I am no pilot; yet, wert thou as far

<br>Dost thou love me? I know thou wilt say 'Ay,'
<br>And I will take thy word: yet if thou swear'st,
<span class='playlinenum'>940</span><br>Thou mayst prove false; at lovers' perjuries

<br>I'll frown and be perverse an say thee nay,
<span class='playlinenum'>945</span><br>So thou wilt woo; but else, not for the world.

<br>Than those that have more cunning to be strange.
<span class='playlinenum'>950</span><br>I should have been more strange, I must confess,

<br>Which the dark night hath so discovered.
<span class='playlinenum'>955</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='956'></a>Lady, by yonder blessed moon I swear

</li></ul>

<span class='playlinenum'>960</span></li></ul>

</li></ul>

<br>Or, if thou wilt, swear by thy gracious self,
<br>Which is the god of my idolatry,
<br>And I'll believe thee.
<span class='playlinenum'>965</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='966'></a>If my heart's dear love&mdash;
</li></ul>

<br>It is too rash, too unadvised, too sudden;
<br>Too like the lightning, which doth cease to be
<span class='playlinenum'>970</span><br>Ere one can say 'It lightens.' Sweet, good night!
<br>This bud of love, by summer's ripening breath,
<br>May prove a beauteous flower when next we meet.
<br>Good night, good night! as sweet repose and rest
<br>Come to thy heart as that within my breast!
<span class='playlinenum'>975</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='976'></a>O, wilt thou leave me so unsatisfied?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='977'></a>What satisfaction canst thou have to-night?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='978'></a>The exchange of thy love's faithful vow for mine.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='979'></a>I gave thee mine before thou didst request it:
<br>And yet I would it were to give again.
<span class='playlinenum'>980</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='981'></a>Wouldst thou withdraw it? for what purpose, love?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='982'></a>But to be frank, and give it thee again.
<br>And yet I wish but for the thing I have:
<br>My bounty is as boundless as the sea,
<br>My love as deep; the more I give to thee,
<span class='playlinenum'>985</span><br>The more I have, for both are infinite.
<br><i>[Nurse calls within]</i>
<br>I hear some noise within; dear love, adieu!
<br>Anon, good nurse! Sweet Montague, be true.
<br>Stay but a little, I will come again.
<span class='playlinenum'>990</span></li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='991'></a>[Exit, above]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='992'></a>O blessed, blessed night! I am afeard.
<br>Being in night, all this is but a dream,
<br>Too flattering-sweet to be substantial.
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='995'></a>[Re-enter JULIET, above]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='996'></a>Three words, dear Romeo, and good night indeed.
<br>If that thy bent of love be honourable,
<br>Thy purpose marriage, send me word to-morrow,
<br>By one that I'll procure to come to thee,
<br>Where and what time thou wilt perform the rite;
<span class='playlinenum'>1000</span><br>And all my fortunes at thy foot I'll lay
<br>And follow thee my lord throughout the world.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Nurse. </strong><a name='1003'></a><i>[Within]</i> Madam!
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='1004'></a>I come, anon.&mdash;But if thou mean'st not well,
<br>I do beseech thee&mdash;
<span class='playlinenum'>1005</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Nurse. </strong><a name='1006'></a><i>[Within]</i> Madam!
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='1007'></a>By and by, I come:&mdash;
<br>To cease thy suit, and leave me to my grief:
<br>To-morrow will I send.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='1010'></a>So thrive my soul&mdash;
<span class='playlinenum'>1010</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='1011'></a>A thousand times good night!
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='1012'></a>[Exit, above]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='1013'></a>A thousand times the worse, to want thy light.
<br>Love goes toward love, as schoolboys from
<br>their books,
<span class='playlinenum'>1015</span><br>But love from love, toward school with heavy looks.
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='1017'></a>[Retiring]
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='1018'></a>[Re-enter JULIET, above]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='1019'></a>Hist! Romeo, hist! O, for a falconer's voice,
<br>To lure this tassel-gentle back again!
<span class='playlinenum'>1020</span><br>Bondage is hoarse, and may not speak aloud;
<br>Else would I tear the cave where Echo lies,
<br>And make her airy tongue more hoarse than mine,
<br>With repetition of my Romeo's name.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='1025'></a>It is my soul that calls upon my name:
<span class='playlinenum'>1025</span><br>How silver-sweet sound lovers' tongues by night,
<br>Like softest music to attending ears!
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='1028'></a>Romeo!
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='1029'></a>My dear?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='1030'></a>At what o'clock to-morrow
<span class='playlinenum'>1030</span><br>Shall I send to thee?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='1032'></a>At the hour of nine.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='1033'></a>I will not fail: 'tis twenty years till then.
<br>I have forgot why I did call thee back.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='1035'></a>Let me stand here till thou remember it.
<span class='playlinenum'>1035</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='1036'></a>I shall forget, to have thee still stand there,
<br>Remembering how I love thy company.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='1038'></a>And I'll still stay, to have thee still forget,
<br>Forgetting any other home but this.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='1040'></a>'Tis almost morning; I would have thee gone:
<span class='playlinenum'>1040</span><br>And yet no further than a wanton's bird;
<br>Who lets it hop a little from her hand,
<br>Like a poor prisoner in his twisted gyves,
<br>And with a silk thread plucks it back again,
<br>So loving-jealous of his liberty.
<span class='playlinenum'>1045</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='1046'></a>I would I were thy bird.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='1047'></a>Sweet, so would I:
<br>Yet I should kill thee with much cherishing.
<br>Good night, good night! parting is such
<br>sweet sorrow,
<span class='playlinenum'>1050</span><br>That I shall say good night till it be morrow.
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='1052'></a>[Exit above]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='1053'></a>Sleep dwell upon thine eyes, peace in thy breast!
<br>Would I were sleep and peace, so sweet to rest!
<br>Hence will I to my ghostly father's cell,
<span class='playlinenum'>1055</span><br>His help to crave, and my dear hap to tell.
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='1057'></a>[Exit]
</li></ul>

<td></li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='1058'></a>[Enter FRIAR LAURENCE, with a basket]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Friar Laurence. </strong><a name='1059'></a>The grey-eyed morn smiles on the frowning night,
<br>Chequering the eastern clouds with streaks of light,
<span class='playlinenum'>1060</span><br>And flecked darkness like a drunkard reels
<br>From forth day's path and Titan's fiery wheels:
<br>Now, ere the sun advance his burning eye,
<br>The day to cheer and night's dank dew to dry,
<br>I must up-fill this osier cage of ours
<span class='playlinenum'>1065</span><br>With baleful weeds and precious-juiced flowers.
<br>The earth that's nature's mother is her tomb;
<br>What is her burying grave that is her womb,
<br>And from her womb children of divers kind
<br>We sucking on her natural bosom find,
<span class='playlinenum'>1070</span><br>Many for many virtues excellent,
<br>None but for some and yet all different.
<br>O, mickle is the powerful grace that lies
<br>In herbs, plants, stones, and their true qualities:
<br>For nought so vile that on the earth doth live
<span class='playlinenum'>1075</span><br>But to the earth some special good doth give,
<br>Nor aught so good but strain'd from that fair use
<br>Revolts from true birth, stumbling on abuse:
<br>Virtue itself turns vice, being misapplied;
<br>And vice sometimes by action dignified.
<span class='playlinenum'>1080</span><br>Within the infant rind of this small flower
<br>Poison hath residence and medicine power:
<br>For this, being smelt, with that part cheers each part;
<br>Being tasted, slays all senses with the heart.
<br>Two such opposed kings encamp them still
<span class='playlinenum'>1085</span><br>In man as well as herbs, grace and rude will;
<br>And where the worser is predominant,
<br>Full soon the canker death eats up that plant.
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='1089'></a>[Enter ROMEO]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='1090'></a>Good morrow, father.
<span class='playlinenum'>1090</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Friar Laurence. </strong><a name='1091'></a>Benedicite!
<br>What early tongue so sweet saluteth me?
<br>Young son, it argues a distemper'd head
<br>So soon to bid good morrow to thy bed:
<br>Care keeps his watch in every old man's eye,
<span class='playlinenum'>1095</span><br>And where care lodges, sleep will never lie;
<br>But where unbruised youth with unstuff'd brain
<br>Doth couch his limbs, there golden sleep doth reign:
<br>Therefore thy earliness doth me assure
<br>Thou art up-roused by some distemperature;
<span class='playlinenum'>1100</span><br>Or if not so, then here I hit it right,
<br>Our Romeo hath not been in bed to-night.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='1103'></a>That last is true; the sweeter rest was mine.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Friar Laurence. </strong><a name='1104'></a>God pardon sin! wast thou with Rosaline?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='1105'></a>With Rosaline, my ghostly father? no;
<span class='playlinenum'>1105</span><br>I have forgot that name, and that name's woe.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Friar Laurence. </strong><a name='1107'></a>That's my good son: but where hast thou been, then?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='1108'></a>I'll tell thee, ere thou ask it me again.
<br>I have been feasting with mine enemy,
<br>Where on a sudden one hath wounded me,
<span class='playlinenum'>1110</span><br>That's by me wounded: both our remedies
<br>Within thy help and holy physic lies:
<br>I bear no hatred, blessed man, for, lo,
<br>My intercession likewise steads my foe.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Friar Laurence. </strong><a name='1115'></a>Be plain, good son, and homely in thy drift;
<span class='playlinenum'>1115</span><br>Riddling confession finds but riddling shrift.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='1117'></a>Then plainly know my heart's dear love is set
<br>On the fair daughter of rich Capulet:
<br>As mine on hers, so hers is set on mine;
<br>And all combined, save what thou must combine
<span class='playlinenum'>1120</span><br>By holy marriage: when and where and how
<br>We met, we woo'd and made exchange of vow,
<br>I'll tell thee as we pass; but this I pray,
<br>That thou consent to marry us to-day.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Friar Laurence. </strong><a name='1125'></a>Holy Saint Francis, what a change is here!
<span class='playlinenum'>1125</span><br>Is Rosaline, whom thou didst love so dear,
<br>So soon forsaken? young men's love then lies
<br>Not truly in their hearts, but in their eyes.
<br>Jesu Maria, what a deal of brine
<br>Hath wash'd thy sallow cheeks for Rosaline!
<span class='playlinenum'>1130</span><br>How much salt water thrown away in waste,
<br>To season love, that of it doth not taste!
<br>The sun not yet thy sighs from heaven clears,
<br>Thy old groans ring yet in my ancient ears;
<br>Lo, here upon thy cheek the stain doth sit
<span class='playlinenum'>1135</span><br>Of an old tear that is not wash'd off yet:
<br>If e'er thou wast thyself and these woes thine,
<br>Thou and these woes were all for Rosaline:
<br>And art thou changed? pronounce this sentence then,
<br>Women may fall, when there's no strength in men.
<span class='playlinenum'>1140</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='1141'></a>Thou chid'st me oft for loving Rosaline.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Friar Laurence. </strong><a name='1142'></a>For doting, not for loving, pupil mine.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='1143'></a>And bad'st me bury love.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Friar Laurence. </strong><a name='1144'></a>Not in a grave,
<br>To lay one in, another out to have.
<span class='playlinenum'>1145</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='1146'></a>I pray thee, chide not; she whom I love now
<br>Doth grace for grace and love for love allow;
<br>The other did not so.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Friar Laurence. </strong><a name='1149'></a>O, she knew well
<br>Thy love did read by rote and could not spell.
<span class='playlinenum'>1150</span><br>But come, young waverer, come, go with me,
<br>In one respect I'll thy assistant be;
<br>For this alliance may so happy prove,
<br>To turn your households' rancour to pure love.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='1155'></a>O, let us hence; I stand on sudden haste.
<span class='playlinenum'>1155</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Friar Laurence. </strong><a name='1156'></a>Wisely and slow; they stumble that run fast.
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='1157'></a>[Exeunt]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Mercutio. </strong><a name='1177'></a>More than prince of cats, I can tell you. O, he is

<span class='playlinenum'>1180</span><br>the third in your bosom: the very butcher of a silk

<span class='playlinenum'>1185</span></li></ul>

</li></ul>

<span class='playlinenum'>1230</span><br>was I with you there for the goose?

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='1232'></a>Thou wast never with me for any thing when thou wast
