<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Mercutio. </strong><a name='1503'></a>Thou art like one of those fellows that when he
<br>enters the confines of a tavern claps me his sword
<br>upon the table and says 'God send me no need of
<span class='playlinenum'>1505</span><br>thee!' and by the operation of the second cup draws
<br>it on the drawer, when indeed there is no need.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Benvolio. </strong><a name='1508'></a>Am I like such a fellow?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Mercutio. </strong><a name='1509'></a>Come, come, thou art as hot a Jack in thy mood as
<br>any in Italy, and as soon moved to be moody, and as
<span class='playlinenum'>1510</span><br>soon moody to be moved.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Benvolio. </strong><a name='1512'></a>And what to?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Mercutio. </strong><a name='1513'></a>Nay, an there were two such, we should have none
<br>shortly, for one would kill the other. Thou! why,
<br>thou wilt quarrel with a man that hath a hair more,
<span class='playlinenum'>1515</span><br>or a hair less, in his beard, than thou hast: thou
<br>wilt quarrel with a man for cracking nuts, having no
<br>other reason but because thou hast hazel eyes: what
<br>eye but such an eye would spy out such a quarrel?
<br>Thy head is as fun of quarrels as an egg is full of
<span class='playlinenum'>1520</span><br>meat, and yet thy head hath been beaten as addle as
<br>an egg for quarrelling: thou hast quarrelled with a
<br>man for coughing in the street, because he hath
<br>wakened thy dog that hath lain asleep in the sun:
<br>didst thou not fall out with a tailor for wearing
<span class='playlinenum'>1525</span><br>his new doublet before Easter? with another, for
<br>tying his new shoes with old riband? and yet thou
<br>wilt tutor me from quarrelling!
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Benvolio. </strong><a name='1529'></a>An I were so apt to quarrel as thou art, any man
<br>should buy the fee-simple of my life for an hour and a quarter.
<span class='playlinenum'>1530</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Mercutio. </strong><a name='1531'></a>The fee-simple! O simple!
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Benvolio. </strong><a name='1532'></a>By my head, here come the Capulets.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Mercutio. </strong><a name='1533'></a>By my heel, I care not.
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='1534'></a>[Enter TYBALT and others]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Tybalt. </strong><a name='1535'></a>Follow me close, for I will speak to them.
<span class='playlinenum'>1535</span><br>Gentlemen, good den: a word with one of you.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Mercutio. </strong><a name='1537'></a>And but one word with one of us? couple it with
<br>something; make it a word and a blow.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Tybalt. </strong><a name='1539'></a>You shall find me apt enough to that, sir, an you
<br>will give me occasion.
<span class='playlinenum'>1540</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Mercutio. </strong><a name='1541'></a>Could you not take some occasion without giving?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Tybalt. </strong><a name='1542'></a>Mercutio, thou consort'st with Romeo,&mdash;
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Mercutio. </strong><a name='1543'></a>Consort! what, dost thou make us minstrels? an
<br>thou make minstrels of us, look to hear nothing but
<br>discords: here's my fiddlestick; here's that shall
<span class='playlinenum'>1545</span><br>make you dance. 'Zounds, consort!
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Benvolio. </strong><a name='1547'></a>We talk here in the public haunt of men:
<br>Either withdraw unto some private place,
<br>And reason coldly of your grievances,
<br>Or else depart; here all eyes gaze on us.
<span class='playlinenum'>1550</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Mercutio. </strong><a name='1551'></a>Men's eyes were made to look, and let them gaze;
<br>I will not budge for no man's pleasure, I.
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='1553'></a>[Enter ROMEO]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Tybalt. </strong><a name='1554'></a>Well, peace be with you, sir: here comes my man.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Mercutio. </strong><a name='1555'></a>But I'll be hanged, sir, if he wear your livery:
<span class='playlinenum'>1555</span><br>Marry, go before to field, he'll be your follower;
<br>Your worship in that sense may call him 'man.'
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Tybalt. </strong><a name='1558'></a>Romeo, the hate I bear thee can afford
<br>No better term than this,&mdash;thou art a villain.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='1560'></a>Tybalt, the reason that I have to love thee
<span class='playlinenum'>1560</span><br>Doth much excuse the appertaining rage
<br>To such a greeting: villain am I none;
<br>Therefore farewell; I see thou know'st me not.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Tybalt. </strong><a name='1564'></a>Boy, this shall not excuse the injuries
<br>That thou hast done me; therefore turn and draw.
<span class='playlinenum'>1565</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='1566'></a>I do protest, I never injured thee,
<br>But love thee better than thou canst devise,
<br>Till thou shalt know the reason of my love:
<br>And so, good Capulet,&mdash;which name I tender
<br>As dearly as my own,&mdash;be satisfied.
<span class='playlinenum'>1570</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Mercutio. </strong><a name='1571'></a>O calm, dishonourable, vile submission!
<br>Alla stoccata carries it away.
<br><i>[Draws]</i>
<br>Tybalt, you rat-catcher, will you walk?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Tybalt. </strong><a name='1575'></a>What wouldst thou have with me?
<span class='playlinenum'>1575</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Mercutio. </strong><a name='1576'></a>Good king of cats, nothing but one of your nine
<br>lives; that I mean to make bold withal, and as you
<br>shall use me hereafter, drybeat the rest of the
<br>eight. Will you pluck your sword out of his pitcher
<br>by the ears? make haste, lest mine be about your
<span class='playlinenum'>1580</span><br>ears ere it be out.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Tybalt. </strong><a name='1582'></a>I am for you.
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='1583'></a>[Drawing]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='1584'></a>Gentle Mercutio, put thy rapier up.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Mercutio. </strong><a name='1585'></a>Come, sir, your passado.
<span class='playlinenum'>1585</span></li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='1586'></a>[They fight]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='1587'></a>Draw, Benvolio; beat down their weapons.
<br>Gentlemen, for shame, forbear this outrage!
<br>Tybalt, Mercutio, the prince expressly hath
<br>Forbidden bandying in Verona streets:
<span class='playlinenum'>1590</span><br>Hold, Tybalt! good Mercutio!
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='1592'></a>[TYBALT under ROMEO's arm stabs MERCUTIO, and flies with his followers]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Mercutio. </strong><a name='1593'></a>I am hurt.
<br>A plague o' both your houses! I am sped.
<br>Is he gone, and hath nothing?
<span class='playlinenum'>1595</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Benvolio. </strong><a name='1596'></a>What, art thou hurt?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Mercutio. </strong><a name='1597'></a>Ay, ay, a scratch, a scratch; marry, 'tis enough.
<br>Where is my page? Go, villain, fetch a surgeon.
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='1599'></a>[Exit Page]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='1600'></a>Courage, man; the hurt cannot be much.
<span class='playlinenum'>1600</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Mercutio. </strong><a name='1601'></a>No, 'tis not so deep as a well, nor so wide as a
<br>church-door; but 'tis enough,'twill serve: ask for
<br>me to-morrow, and you shall find me a grave man. I
<br>am peppered, I warrant, for this world. A plague o'
<br>both your houses! 'Zounds, a dog, a rat, a mouse, a
<span class='playlinenum'>1605</span><br>cat, to scratch a man to death! a braggart, a
<br>rogue, a villain, that fights by the book of
<br>arithmetic! Why the devil came you between us? I
<br>was hurt under your arm.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='1610'></a>I thought all for the best.
<span class='playlinenum'>1610</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Mercutio. </strong><a name='1611'></a>Help me into some house, Benvolio,
<br>Or I shall faint. A plague o' both your houses!
<br>They have made worms' meat of me: I have it,
<br>And soundly too: your houses!
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='1615'></a>[Exeunt MERCUTIO and BENVOLIO]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='1616'></a>This gentleman, the prince's near ally,
<br>My very friend, hath got his mortal hurt
<br>In my behalf; my reputation stain'd
<br>With Tybalt's slander,&mdash;Tybalt, that an hour
<br>Hath been my kinsman! O sweet Juliet,
<span class='playlinenum'>1620</span><br>Thy beauty hath made me effeminate
<br>And in my temper soften'd valour's steel!
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='1623'></a>[Re-enter BENVOLIO]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Benvolio. </strong><a name='1624'></a>O Romeo, Romeo, brave Mercutio's dead!
<br>That gallant spirit hath aspired the clouds,
<span class='playlinenum'>1625</span><br>Which too untimely here did scorn the earth.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='1627'></a>This day's black fate on more days doth depend;
<br>This but begins the woe, others must end.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Benvolio. </strong><a name='1629'></a>Here comes the furious Tybalt back again.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='1630'></a>Alive, in triumph! and Mercutio slain!
<span class='playlinenum'>1630</span><br>Away to heaven, respective lenity,
<br>And fire-eyed fury be my conduct now!
<br><i>[Re-enter TYBALT]</i>
<br>Now, Tybalt, take the villain back again,
<br>That late thou gavest me; for Mercutio's soul
<span class='playlinenum'>1635</span><br>Is but a little way above our heads,
<br>Staying for thine to keep him company:
<br>Either thou, or I, or both, must go with him.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Tybalt. </strong><a name='1639'></a>Thou, wretched boy, that didst consort him here,
<br>Shalt with him hence.
<span class='playlinenum'>1640</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='1641'></a>This shall determine that.
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='1642'></a>[They fight; TYBALT falls]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Benvolio. </strong><a name='1643'></a>Romeo, away, be gone!
<br>The citizens are up, and Tybalt slain.
<br>Stand not amazed: the prince will doom thee death,
<span class='playlinenum'>1645</span><br>If thou art taken: hence, be gone, away!
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='1647'></a>O, I am fortune's fool!
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Benvolio. </strong><a name='1648'></a>Why dost thou stay?
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='1649'></a>[Exit ROMEO]
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='1650'></a>[Enter Citizens, &c]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>First Citizen. </strong><a name='1651'></a>Which way ran he that kill'd Mercutio?
<br>Tybalt, that murderer, which way ran he?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Benvolio. </strong><a name='1653'></a>There lies that Tybalt.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>First Citizen. </strong><a name='1654'></a>Up, sir, go with me;
<br>I charge thee in the princes name, obey.
<span class='playlinenum'>1655</span><br><i>[Enter Prince, attended; MONTAGUE, CAPULET, their]</i>
<br>Wives, and others]</i>
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Prince Escalus. </strong><a name='1658'></a>Where are the vile beginners of this fray?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Benvolio. </strong><a name='1659'></a>O noble prince, I can discover all
<br>The unlucky manage of this fatal brawl:
<span class='playlinenum'>1660</span><br>There lies the man, slain by young Romeo,
<br>That slew thy kinsman, brave Mercutio.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Lady Capulet. </strong><a name='1663'></a>Tybalt, my cousin! O my brother's child!
<br>O prince! O cousin! husband! O, the blood is spilt
<br>O my dear kinsman! Prince, as thou art true,
<span class='playlinenum'>1665</span><br>For blood of ours, shed blood of Montague.
<br>O cousin, cousin!
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Prince Escalus. </strong><a name='1668'></a>Benvolio, who began this bloody fray?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Benvolio. </strong><a name='1669'></a>Tybalt, here slain, whom Romeo's hand did slay;
<br>Romeo that spoke him fair, bade him bethink
<span class='playlinenum'>1670</span><br>How nice the quarrel was, and urged withal
<br>Your high displeasure: all this uttered
<br>With gentle breath, calm look, knees humbly bow'd,
<br>Could not take truce with the unruly spleen
<br>Of Tybalt deaf to peace, but that he tilts
<span class='playlinenum'>1675</span><br>With piercing steel at bold Mercutio's breast,
<br>Who all as hot, turns deadly point to point,
<br>And, with a martial scorn, with one hand beats
<br>Cold death aside, and with the other sends
<br>It back to Tybalt, whose dexterity,
<span class='playlinenum'>1680</span><br>Retorts it: Romeo he cries aloud,
<br>'Hold, friends! friends, part!' and, swifter than
<br>his tongue,
<br>His agile arm beats down their fatal points,
<br>And 'twixt them rushes; underneath whose arm
<span class='playlinenum'>1685</span><br>An envious thrust from Tybalt hit the life
<br>Of stout Mercutio, and then Tybalt fled;
<br>But by and by comes back to Romeo,
<br>Who had but newly entertain'd revenge,
<br>And to 't they go like lightning, for, ere I
<span class='playlinenum'>1690</span><br>Could draw to part them, was stout Tybalt slain.
<br>And, as he fell, did Romeo turn and fly.
<br>This is the truth, or let Benvolio die.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Lady Capulet. </strong><a name='1694'></a>He is a kinsman to the Montague;
<br>Affection makes him false; he speaks not true:
<span class='playlinenum'>1695</span><br>Some twenty of them fought in this black strife,
<br>And all those twenty could but kill one life.
<br>I beg for justice, which thou, prince, must give;
<br>Romeo slew Tybalt, Romeo must not live.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Prince Escalus. </strong><a name='1700'></a>Romeo slew him, he slew Mercutio;
<span class='playlinenum'>1700</span><br>Who now the price of his dear blood doth owe?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Montague. </strong><a name='1702'></a>Not Romeo, prince, he was Mercutio's friend;
<br>His fault concludes but what the law should end,
<br>The life of Tybalt.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Prince Escalus. </strong><a name='1705'></a>And for that offence
<span class='playlinenum'>1705</span><br>Immediately we do exile him hence:
<br>I have an interest in your hate's proceeding,
<br>My blood for your rude brawls doth lie a-bleeding;
<br>But I'll amerce you with so strong a fine
<br>That you shall all repent the loss of mine:
<span class='playlinenum'>1710</span><br>I will be deaf to pleading and excuses;
<br>Nor tears nor prayers shall purchase out abuses:
<br>Therefore use none: let Romeo hence in haste,
<br>Else, when he's found, that hour is his last.
<br>Bear hence this body and attend our will:
<span class='playlinenum'>1715</span><br>Mercy but murders, pardoning those that kill.
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='1717'></a>[Exeunt]
</li></ul>

<td></li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='1718'></a>[Enter JULIET]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='1719'></a>Gallop apace, you fiery-footed steeds,
<br>Towards Phoebus' lodging: such a wagoner
<span class='playlinenum'>1720</span><br>As Phaethon would whip you to the west,
<br>And bring in cloudy night immediately.
<br>Spread thy close curtain, love-performing night,
<br>That runaway's eyes may wink and Romeo
<br>Leap to these arms, untalk'd of and unseen.
<span class='playlinenum'>1725</span><br>Lovers can see to do their amorous rites
<br>By their own beauties; or, if love be blind,
<br>It best agrees with night. Come, civil night,
<br>Thou sober-suited matron, all in black,
<br>And learn me how to lose a winning match,
<span class='playlinenum'>1730</span><br>Play'd for a pair of stainless maidenhoods:
<br>Hood my unmann'd blood, bating in my cheeks,
<br>With thy black mantle; till strange love, grown bold,
<br>Think true love acted simple modesty.
<br>Come, night; come, Romeo; come, thou day in night;
<span class='playlinenum'>1735</span><br>For thou wilt lie upon the wings of night
<br>Whiter than new snow on a raven's back.
<br>Come, gentle night, come, loving, black-brow'd night,
<br>Give me my Romeo; and, when he shall die,
<br>Take him and cut him out in little stars,
<span class='playlinenum'>1740</span><br>And he will make the face of heaven so fine
<br>That all the world will be in love with night
<br>And pay no worship to the garish sun.
<br>O, I have bought the mansion of a love,
<br>But not possess'd it, and, though I am sold,
<span class='playlinenum'>1745</span><br>Not yet enjoy'd: so tedious is this day
<br>As is the night before some festival
<br>To an impatient child that hath new robes
<br>And may not wear them. O, here comes my nurse,
<br>And she brings news; and every tongue that speaks
<span class='playlinenum'>1750</span><br>But Romeo's name speaks heavenly eloquence.
<br><i>[Enter Nurse, with cords]</i>
<br>Now, nurse, what news? What hast thou there? the cords
<br>That Romeo bid thee fetch?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Nurse. </strong><a name='1755'></a>Ay, ay, the cords.
<span class='playlinenum'>1755</span></li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='1756'></a>[Throws them down]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='1757'></a>Ay me! what news? why dost thou wring thy hands?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Nurse. </strong><a name='1758'></a>Ah, well-a-day! he's dead, he's dead, he's dead!
<br>We are undone, lady, we are undone!
<br>Alack the day! he's gone, he's kill'd, he's dead!
<span class='playlinenum'>1760</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='1761'></a>Can heaven be so envious?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Nurse. </strong><a name='1762'></a>Romeo can,
<br>Though heaven cannot: O Romeo, Romeo!
<br>Who ever would have thought it? Romeo!
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='1765'></a>What devil art thou, that dost torment me thus?
<span class='playlinenum'>1765</span><br>This torture should be roar'd in dismal hell.
<br>Hath Romeo slain himself? say thou but 'I,'
<br>And that bare vowel 'I' shall poison more
<br>Than the death-darting eye of cockatrice:
<br>I am not I, if there be such an I;
<span class='playlinenum'>1770</span><br>Or those eyes shut, that make thee answer 'I.'
<br>If he be slain, say 'I'; or if not, no:
<br>Brief sounds determine of my weal or woe.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Nurse. </strong><a name='1774'></a>I saw the wound, I saw it with mine eyes,&mdash;
<br>God save the mark!&mdash;here on his manly breast:
<span class='playlinenum'>1775</span><br>A piteous corse, a bloody piteous corse;
<br>Pale, pale as ashes, all bedaub'd in blood,
<br>All in gore-blood; I swounded at the sight.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='1779'></a>O, break, my heart! poor bankrupt, break at once!
<br>To prison, eyes, ne'er look on liberty!
<span class='playlinenum'>1780</span><br>Vile earth, to earth resign; end motion here;
<br>And thou and Romeo press one heavy bier!
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Nurse. </strong><a name='1783'></a>O Tybalt, Tybalt, the best friend I had!
<br>O courteous Tybalt! honest gentleman!
<br>That ever I should live to see thee dead!
<span class='playlinenum'>1785</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='1786'></a>What storm is this that blows so contrary?
<br>Is Romeo slaughter'd, and is Tybalt dead?
<br>My dear-loved cousin, and my dearer lord?
<br>Then, dreadful trumpet, sound the general doom!
<br>For who is living, if those two are gone?
<span class='playlinenum'>1790</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Nurse. </strong><a name='1791'></a>Tybalt is gone, and Romeo banished;
<br>Romeo that kill'd him, he is banished.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='1793'></a>O God! did Romeo's hand shed Tybalt's blood?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Nurse. </strong><a name='1794'></a>It did, it did; alas the day, it did!
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='1795'></a>O serpent heart, hid with a flowering face!
<span class='playlinenum'>1795</span><br>Did ever dragon keep so fair a cave?
<br>Beautiful tyrant! fiend angelical!
<br>Dove-feather'd raven! wolvish-ravening lamb!
<br>Despised substance of divinest show!
<br>Just opposite to what thou justly seem'st,
<span class='playlinenum'>1800</span><br>A damned saint, an honourable villain!
<br>O nature, what hadst thou to do in hell,
<br>When thou didst bower the spirit of a fiend
<br>In moral paradise of such sweet flesh?
<br>Was ever book containing such vile matter
<span class='playlinenum'>1805</span><br>So fairly bound? O that deceit should dwell
<br>In such a gorgeous palace!
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Nurse. </strong><a name='1808'></a>There's no trust,
<br>No faith, no honesty in men; all perjured,
<br>All forsworn, all naught, all dissemblers.
<span class='playlinenum'>1810</span><br>Ah, where's my man? give me some aqua vitae:
<br>These griefs, these woes, these sorrows make me old.
<br>Shame come to Romeo!
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='1814'></a>Blister'd be thy tongue
<br>For such a wish! he was not born to shame:
<span class='playlinenum'>1815</span><br>Upon his brow shame is ashamed to sit;
<br>For 'tis a throne where honour may be crown'd
<br>Sole monarch of the universal earth.
<br>O, what a beast was I to chide at him!
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Nurse. </strong><a name='1820'></a>Will you speak well of him that kill'd your cousin?
<span class='playlinenum'>1820</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='1821'></a>Shall I speak ill of him that is my husband?
<br>Ah, poor my lord, what tongue shall smooth thy name,
<br>When I, thy three-hours wife, have mangled it?
<br>But, wherefore, villain, didst thou kill my cousin?
<br>That villain cousin would have kill'd my husband:
<span class='playlinenum'>1825</span><br>Back, foolish tears, back to your native spring;
<br>Your tributary drops belong to woe,
<br>Which you, mistaking, offer up to joy.
<br>My husband lives, that Tybalt would have slain;
<br>And Tybalt's dead, that would have slain my husband:
<span class='playlinenum'>1830</span><br>All this is comfort; wherefore weep I then?
<br>Some word there was, worser than Tybalt's death,
<br>That murder'd me: I would forget it fain;
<br>But, O, it presses to my memory,
<br>Like damned guilty deeds to sinners' minds:
<span class='playlinenum'>1835</span><br>'Tybalt is dead, and Romeo&mdash;banished;'
<br>That 'banished,' that one word 'banished,'
<br>Hath slain ten thousand Tybalts. Tybalt's death
<br>Was woe enough, if it had ended there:
<br>Or, if sour woe delights in fellowship
<span class='playlinenum'>1840</span><br>And needly will be rank'd with other griefs,
<br>Why follow'd not, when she said 'Tybalt's dead,'
<br>Thy father, or thy mother, nay, or both,
<br>Which modern lamentations might have moved?
<br>But with a rear-ward following Tybalt's death,
<span class='playlinenum'>1845</span><br>'Romeo is banished,' to speak that word,
<br>Is father, mother, Tybalt, Romeo, Juliet,
<br>All slain, all dead. 'Romeo is banished!'
<br>There is no end, no limit, measure, bound,
<br>In that word's death; no words can that woe sound.
<span class='playlinenum'>1850</span><br>Where is my father, and my mother, nurse?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Nurse. </strong><a name='1852'></a>Weeping and wailing over Tybalt's corse:
<br>Will you go to them? I will bring you thither.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='1854'></a>Wash they his wounds with tears: mine shall be spent,
<br>When theirs are dry, for Romeo's banishment.
<span class='playlinenum'>1855</span><br>Take up those cords: poor ropes, you are beguiled,
<br>Both you and I; for Romeo is exiled:
<br>He made you for a highway to my bed;
<br>But I, a maid, die maiden-widowed.
<br>Come, cords, come, nurse; I'll to my wedding-bed;
<span class='playlinenum'>1860</span><br>And death, not Romeo, take my maidenhead!
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Nurse. </strong><a name='1862'></a>Hie to your chamber: I'll find Romeo
<br>To comfort you: I wot well where he is.
<br>Hark ye, your Romeo will be here at night:
<br>I'll to him; he is hid at Laurence' cell.
<span class='playlinenum'>1865</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='1866'></a>O, find him! give this ring to my true knight,
<br>And bid him come to take his last farewell.
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='1868'></a>[Exeunt]
</li></ul>

<p class='stagedir' style='text-align:center'><strong>Friar Laurence&#8217;s cell.</strong></p>

<table width='600' cellspacing='30'>
<tr>
<td></li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='1869'></a>[Enter FRIAR LAURENCE]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Friar Laurence. </strong><a name='1870'></a>Romeo, come forth; come forth, thou fearful man:
<span class='playlinenum'>1870</span><br>Affliction is enamour'd of thy parts,
<br>And thou art wedded to calamity.
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='1873'></a>[Enter ROMEO]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='1874'></a>Father, what news? what is the prince's doom?
<br>What sorrow craves acquaintance at my hand,
<span class='playlinenum'>1875</span><br>That I yet know not?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Friar Laurence. </strong><a name='1877'></a>Too familiar
<br>Is my dear son with such sour company:
<br>I bring thee tidings of the prince's doom.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='1880'></a>What less than dooms-day is the prince's doom?
<span class='playlinenum'>1880</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Friar Laurence. </strong><a name='1881'></a>A gentler judgment vanish'd from his lips,
<br>Not body's death, but body's banishment.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='1883'></a>Ha, banishment! be merciful, say 'death;'
<br>For exile hath more terror in his look,
<br>Much more than death: do not say 'banishment.'
<span class='playlinenum'>1885</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Friar Laurence. </strong><a name='1886'></a>Hence from Verona art thou banished:
<br>Be patient, for the world is broad and wide.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='1888'></a>There is no world without Verona walls,
<br>But purgatory, torture, hell itself.
<br>Hence-banished is banish'd from the world,
<span class='playlinenum'>1890</span><br>And world's exile is death: then banished,
<br>Is death mis-term'd: calling death banishment,
<br>Thou cutt'st my head off with a golden axe,
<br>And smilest upon the stroke that murders me.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Friar Laurence. </strong><a name='1895'></a>O deadly sin! O rude unthankfulness!
<span class='playlinenum'>1895</span><br>Thy fault our law calls death; but the kind prince,
<br>Taking thy part, hath rush'd aside the law,
<br>And turn'd that black word death to banishment:
<br>This is dear mercy, and thou seest it not.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='1900'></a>'Tis torture, and not mercy: heaven is here,
<span class='playlinenum'>1900</span><br>Where Juliet lives; and every cat and dog
<br>And little mouse, every unworthy thing,
<br>Live here in heaven and may look on her;
<br>But Romeo may not: more validity,
<br>More honourable state, more courtship lives
<span class='playlinenum'>1905</span><br>In carrion-flies than Romeo: they my seize
<br>On the white wonder of dear Juliet's hand
<br>And steal immortal blessing from her lips,
<br>Who even in pure and vestal modesty,
<br>Still blush, as thinking their own kisses sin;
<span class='playlinenum'>1910</span><br>But Romeo may not; he is banished:
<br>Flies may do this, but I from this must fly:
<br>They are free men, but I am banished.
<br>And say'st thou yet that exile is not death?
<br>Hadst thou no poison mix'd, no sharp-ground knife,
<span class='playlinenum'>1915</span><br>No sudden mean of death, though ne'er so mean,
<br>But 'banished' to kill me?&mdash;'banished'?
<br>O friar, the damned use that word in hell;
<br>Howlings attend it: how hast thou the heart,
<br>Being a divine, a ghostly confessor,
<span class='playlinenum'>1920</span><br>A sin-absolver, and my friend profess'd,
<br>To mangle me with that word 'banished'?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Friar Laurence. </strong><a name='1923'></a>Thou fond mad man, hear me but speak a word.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='1924'></a>O, thou wilt speak again of banishment.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Friar Laurence. </strong><a name='1925'></a>I'll give thee armour to keep off that word:
<span class='playlinenum'>1925</span><br>Adversity's sweet milk, philosophy,
<br>To comfort thee, though thou art banished.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='1928'></a>Yet 'banished'? Hang up philosophy!
<br>Unless philosophy can make a Juliet,
<br>Displant a town, reverse a prince's doom,
<span class='playlinenum'>1930</span><br>It helps not, it prevails not: talk no more.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Friar Laurence. </strong><a name='1932'></a>O, then I see that madmen have no ears.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='1933'></a>How should they, when that wise men have no eyes?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Friar Laurence. </strong><a name='1934'></a>Let me dispute with thee of thy estate.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='1935'></a>Thou canst not speak of that thou dost not feel:
<span class='playlinenum'>1935</span><br>Wert thou as young as I, Juliet thy love,
<br>An hour but married, Tybalt murdered,
<br>Doting like me and like me banished,
<br>Then mightst thou speak, then mightst thou tear thy hair,
<br>And fall upon the ground, as I do now,
<span class='playlinenum'>1940</span><br>Taking the measure of an unmade grave.
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='1942'></a>[Knocking within]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Friar Laurence. </strong><a name='1943'></a>Arise; one knocks; good Romeo, hide thyself.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='1944'></a>Not I; unless the breath of heartsick groans,
<br>Mist-like, infold me from the search of eyes.
<span class='playlinenum'>1945</span></li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='1946'></a>[Knocking]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Friar Laurence. </strong><a name='1947'></a>Hark, how they knock! Who's there? Romeo, arise;
<br>Thou wilt be taken. Stay awhile! Stand up;
<br><i>[Knocking]</i>
<br>Run to my study. By and by! God's will,
<span class='playlinenum'>1950</span><br>What simpleness is this! I come, I come!
<br><i>[Knocking]</i>
<br>Who knocks so hard? whence come you? what's your will?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Nurse. </strong><a name='1954'></a><i>[Within]</i> Let me come in, and you shall know
<br>my errand;
<span class='playlinenum'>1955</span><br>I come from Lady Juliet.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Friar Laurence. </strong><a name='1957'></a>Welcome, then.
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='1958'></a>[Enter Nurse]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Nurse. </strong><a name='1959'></a>O holy friar, O, tell me, holy friar,
<br>Where is my lady's lord, where's Romeo?
<span class='playlinenum'>1960</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Friar Laurence. </strong><a name='1961'></a>There on the ground, with his own tears made drunk.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Nurse. </strong><a name='1962'></a>O, he is even in my mistress' case,
<br>Just in her case! O woful sympathy!
<br>Piteous predicament! Even so lies she,
<br>Blubbering and weeping, weeping and blubbering.
<span class='playlinenum'>1965</span><br>Stand up, stand up; stand, and you be a man:
<br>For Juliet's sake, for her sake, rise and stand;
<br>Why should you fall into so deep an O?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='1969'></a>Nurse!
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Nurse. </strong><a name='1970'></a>Ah sir! ah sir! Well, death's the end of all.
<span class='playlinenum'>1970</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='1971'></a>Spakest thou of Juliet? how is it with her?
<br>Doth she not think me an old murderer,
<br>Now I have stain'd the childhood of our joy
<br>With blood removed but little from her own?
<br>Where is she? and how doth she? and what says
<span class='playlinenum'>1975</span><br>My conceal'd lady to our cancell'd love?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Nurse. </strong><a name='1977'></a>O, she says nothing, sir, but weeps and weeps;
<br>And now falls on her bed; and then starts up,
<br>And Tybalt calls; and then on Romeo cries,
<br>And then down falls again.
<span class='playlinenum'>1980</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='1981'></a>As if that name,
<br>Shot from the deadly level of a gun,
<br>Did murder her; as that name's cursed hand
<br>Murder'd her kinsman. O, tell me, friar, tell me,
<br>In what vile part of this anatomy
<span class='playlinenum'>1985</span><br>Doth my name lodge? tell me, that I may sack
<br>The hateful mansion.
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='1988'></a>[Drawing his sword]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Friar Laurence. </strong><a name='1989'></a>Hold thy desperate hand:
<br>Art thou a man? thy form cries out thou art:
<span class='playlinenum'>1990</span><br>Thy tears are womanish; thy wild acts denote
<br>The unreasonable fury of a beast:
<br>Unseemly woman in a seeming man!
<br>Or ill-beseeming beast in seeming both!
<br>Thou hast amazed me: by my holy order,
<span class='playlinenum'>1995</span><br>I thought thy disposition better temper'd.
<br>Hast thou slain Tybalt? wilt thou slay thyself?
<br>And stay thy lady too that lives in thee,
<br>By doing damned hate upon thyself?
<br>Why rail'st thou on thy birth, the heaven, and earth?
<span class='playlinenum'>2000</span><br>Since birth, and heaven, and earth, all three do meet
<br>In thee at once; which thou at once wouldst lose.
<br>Fie, fie, thou shamest thy shape, thy love, thy wit;
<br>Which, like a usurer, abound'st in all,
<br>And usest none in that true use indeed
<span class='playlinenum'>2005</span><br>Which should bedeck thy shape, thy love, thy wit:
<br>Thy noble shape is but a form of wax,
<br>Digressing from the valour of a man;
<br>Thy dear love sworn but hollow perjury,
<br>Killing that love which thou hast vow'd to cherish;
<span class='playlinenum'>2010</span><br>Thy wit, that ornament to shape and love,
<br>Misshapen in the conduct of them both,
<br>Like powder in a skitless soldier's flask,
<br>Is set afire by thine own ignorance,
<br>And thou dismember'd with thine own defence.
<span class='playlinenum'>2015</span><br>What, rouse thee, man! thy Juliet is alive,
<br>For whose dear sake thou wast but lately dead;
<br>There art thou happy: Tybalt would kill thee,
<br>But thou slew'st Tybalt; there are thou happy too:
<br>The law that threaten'd death becomes thy friend
<span class='playlinenum'>2020</span><br>And turns it to exile; there art thou happy:
<br>A pack of blessings lights up upon thy back;
<br>Happiness courts thee in her best array;
<br>But, like a misbehaved and sullen wench,
<br>Thou pout'st upon thy fortune and thy love:
<span class='playlinenum'>2025</span><br>Take heed, take heed, for such die miserable.
<br>Go, get thee to thy love, as was decreed,
<br>Ascend her chamber, hence and comfort her:
<br>But look thou stay not till the watch be set,
<br>For then thou canst not pass to Mantua;
<span class='playlinenum'>2030</span><br>Where thou shalt live, till we can find a time
<br>To blaze your marriage, reconcile your friends,
<br>Beg pardon of the prince, and call thee back
<br>With twenty hundred thousand times more joy
<br>Than thou went'st forth in lamentation.
<span class='playlinenum'>2035</span><br>Go before, nurse: commend me to thy lady;
<br>And bid her hasten all the house to bed,
<br>Which heavy sorrow makes them apt unto:
<br>Romeo is coming.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Nurse. </strong><a name='2040'></a>O Lord, I could have stay'd here all the night
<span class='playlinenum'>2040</span><br>To hear good counsel: O, what learning is!
<br>My lord, I'll tell my lady you will come.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='2043'></a>Do so, and bid my sweet prepare to chide.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Nurse. </strong><a name='2044'></a>Here, sir, a ring she bid me give you, sir:
<br>Hie you, make haste, for it grows very late.
<span class='playlinenum'>2045</span></li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='2046'></a>[Exit]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='2047'></a>How well my comfort is revived by this!
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Friar Laurence. </strong><a name='2048'></a>Go hence; good night; and here stands all your state:
<br>Either be gone before the watch be set,
<br>Or by the break of day disguised from hence:
<span class='playlinenum'>2050</span><br>Sojourn in Mantua; I'll find out your man,
<br>And he shall signify from time to time
<br>Every good hap to you that chances here:
<br>Give me thy hand; 'tis late: farewell; good night.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='2055'></a>But that a joy past joy calls out on me,
<span class='playlinenum'>2055</span><br>It were a grief, so brief to part with thee: Farewell.
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='2057'></a>[Exeunt]
</li></ul>

<tr>
<td></li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='2058'></a>[Enter CAPULET, LADY CAPULET, and PARIS]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Capulet. </strong><a name='2059'></a>Things have fall'n out, sir, so unluckily,
<br>That we have had no time to move our daughter:
<span class='playlinenum'>2060</span><br>Look you, she loved her kinsman Tybalt dearly,
<br>And so did I:&mdash;Well, we were born to die.
<br>'Tis very late, she'll not come down to-night:
<br>I promise you, but for your company,
<br>I would have been a-bed an hour ago.
<span class='playlinenum'>2065</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Paris. </strong><a name='2066'></a>These times of woe afford no time to woo.
<br>Madam, good night: commend me to your daughter.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Lady Capulet. </strong><a name='2068'></a>I will, and know her mind early to-morrow;
<br>To-night she is mew'd up to her heaviness.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Capulet. </strong><a name='2070'></a>Sir Paris, I will make a desperate tender
<span class='playlinenum'>2070</span><br>Of my child's love: I think she will be ruled
<br>In all respects by me; nay, more, I doubt it not.
<br>Wife, go you to her ere you go to bed;
<br>Acquaint her here of my son Paris' love;
<br>And bid her, mark you me, on Wednesday next&mdash;
<span class='playlinenum'>2075</span><br>But, soft! what day is this?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Paris. </strong><a name='2077'></a>Monday, my lord,
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Capulet. </strong><a name='2078'></a>Monday! ha, ha! Well, Wednesday is too soon,
<br>O' Thursday let it be: o' Thursday, tell her,
<br>She shall be married to this noble earl.
<span class='playlinenum'>2080</span><br>Will you be ready? do you like this haste?
<br>We'll keep no great ado,&mdash;a friend or two;
<br>For, hark you, Tybalt being slain so late,
<br>It may be thought we held him carelessly,
<br>Being our kinsman, if we revel much:
<span class='playlinenum'>2085</span><br>Therefore we'll have some half a dozen friends,
<br>And there an end. But what say you to Thursday?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Paris. </strong><a name='2088'></a>My lord, I would that Thursday were to-morrow.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Capulet. </strong><a name='2089'></a>Well get you gone: o' Thursday be it, then.
<br>Go you to Juliet ere you go to bed,
<span class='playlinenum'>2090</span><br>Prepare her, wife, against this wedding-day.
<br>Farewell, my lord. Light to my chamber, ho!
<br>Afore me! it is so very very late,
<br>That we may call it early by and by.
<br>Good night.
<span class='playlinenum'>2095</span></li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='2096'></a>[Exeunt]
</li></ul>


</td>
</tr>

<td>
<p class='playsubhead'>Act III, Scene 5</p>
<p class='stagedir' style='text-align:center'><strong>Capulet&#8217;s orchard.</strong></p>
</td>
<td>
&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;
</td>
<td width='150' align='right' valign='middle'>&nbsp;
</td>

<div align='left'>
<table width='600' cellspacing='30'>
<tr>
<td></li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='2097'></a>[Enter ROMEO and JULIET above, at the window]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='2098'></a>Wilt thou be gone? it is not yet near day:
<br>It was the nightingale, and not the lark,
<br>That pierced the fearful hollow of thine ear;
<span class='playlinenum'>2100</span><br>Nightly she sings on yon pomegranate-tree:
<br>Believe me, love, it was the nightingale.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='2103'></a>It was the lark, the herald of the morn,
<br>No nightingale: look, love, what envious streaks
<br>Do lace the severing clouds in yonder east:
<span class='playlinenum'>2105</span><br>Night's candles are burnt out, and jocund day
<br>Stands tiptoe on the misty mountain tops.
<br>I must be gone and live, or stay and die.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='2109'></a>Yon light is not day-light, I know it, I:
<br>It is some meteor that the sun exhales,
<span class='playlinenum'>2110</span><br>To be to thee this night a torch-bearer,
<br>And light thee on thy way to Mantua:
<br>Therefore stay yet; thou need'st not to be gone.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='2114'></a>Let me be ta'en, let me be put to death;
<br>I am content, so thou wilt have it so.
<span class='playlinenum'>2115</span><br>I'll say yon grey is not the morning's eye,
<br>'Tis but the pale reflex of Cynthia's brow;
<br>Nor that is not the lark, whose notes do beat
<br>The vaulty heaven so high above our heads:
<br>I have more care to stay than will to go:
<span class='playlinenum'>2120</span><br>Come, death, and welcome! Juliet wills it so.
<br>How is't, my soul? let's talk; it is not day.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='2123'></a>It is, it is: hie hence, be gone, away!
<br>It is the lark that sings so out of tune,
<br>Straining harsh discords and unpleasing sharps.
<span class='playlinenum'>2125</span><br>Some say the lark makes sweet division;
<br>This doth not so, for she divideth us:
<br>Some say the lark and loathed toad change eyes,
<br>O, now I would they had changed voices too!
<br>Since arm from arm that voice doth us affray,
<span class='playlinenum'>2130</span><br>Hunting thee hence with hunt's-up to the day,
<br>O, now be gone; more light and light it grows.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='2133'></a>More light and light; more dark and dark our woes!
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='2134'></a>[Enter Nurse, to the chamber]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Nurse. </strong><a name='2135'></a>Madam!
<span class='playlinenum'>2135</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='2136'></a>Nurse?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Nurse. </strong><a name='2137'></a>Your lady mother is coming to your chamber:
<br>The day is broke; be wary, look about.
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='2139'></a>[Exit]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='2140'></a>Then, window, let day in, and let life out.
<span class='playlinenum'>2140</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='2141'></a>Farewell, farewell! one kiss, and I'll descend.
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='2142'></a>[He goeth down]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='2143'></a>Art thou gone so? love, lord, ay, husband, friend!
<br>I must hear from thee every day in the hour,
<br>For in a minute there are many days:
<span class='playlinenum'>2145</span><br>O, by this count I shall be much in years
<br>Ere I again behold my Romeo!
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='2148'></a>Farewell!
<br>I will omit no opportunity
<br>That may convey my greetings, love, to thee.
<span class='playlinenum'>2150</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='2151'></a>O think'st thou we shall ever meet again?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='2152'></a>I doubt it not; and all these woes shall serve
<br>For sweet discourses in our time to come.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='2154'></a>O God, I have an ill-divining soul!
<br>Methinks I see thee, now thou art below,
<span class='playlinenum'>2155</span><br>As one dead in the bottom of a tomb:
<br>Either my eyesight fails, or thou look'st pale.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='2158'></a>And trust me, love, in my eye so do you:
<br>Dry sorrow drinks our blood. Adieu, adieu!
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='2160'></a>[Exit]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='2161'></a>O fortune, fortune! all men call thee fickle:
<br>If thou art fickle, what dost thou with him.
<br>That is renown'd for faith? Be fickle, fortune;
<br>For then, I hope, thou wilt not keep him long,
<br>But send him back.
<span class='playlinenum'>2165</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Lady Capulet. </strong><a name='2166'></a><i>[Within]</i> Ho, daughter! are you up?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='2167'></a>Who is't that calls? is it my lady mother?
<br>Is she not down so late, or up so early?
<br>What unaccustom'd cause procures her hither?
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='2170'></a>[Enter LADY CAPULET]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Lady Capulet. </strong><a name='2171'></a>Why, how now, Juliet!
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='2172'></a>Madam, I am not well.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Lady Capulet. </strong><a name='2173'></a>Evermore weeping for your cousin's death?
<br>What, wilt thou wash him from his grave with tears?
<br>An if thou couldst, thou couldst not make him live;
<span class='playlinenum'>2175</span><br>Therefore, have done: some grief shows much of love;
<br>But much of grief shows still some want of wit.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='2178'></a>Yet let me weep for such a feeling loss.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Lady Capulet. </strong><a name='2179'></a>So shall you feel the loss, but not the friend
<br>Which you weep for.
<span class='playlinenum'>2180</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='2181'></a>Feeling so the loss,
<br>Cannot choose but ever weep the friend.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Lady Capulet. </strong><a name='2183'></a>Well, girl, thou weep'st not so much for his death,
<br>As that the villain lives which slaughter'd him.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='2185'></a>What villain madam?
<span class='playlinenum'>2185</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Lady Capulet. </strong><a name='2186'></a>That same villain, Romeo.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='2187'></a><i>[Aside]</i> Villain and he be many miles asunder.&mdash;
<br>God Pardon him! I do, with all my heart;
<br>And yet no man like he doth grieve my heart.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Lady Capulet. </strong><a name='2190'></a>That is, because the traitor murderer lives.
<span class='playlinenum'>2190</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='2191'></a>Ay, madam, from the reach of these my hands:
<br>Would none but I might venge my cousin's death!
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Lady Capulet. </strong><a name='2193'></a>We will have vengeance for it, fear thou not:
<br>Then weep no more. I'll send to one in Mantua,
<br>Where that same banish'd runagate doth live,
<span class='playlinenum'>2195</span><br>Shall give him such an unaccustom'd dram,
<br>That he shall soon keep Tybalt company:
<br>And then, I hope, thou wilt be satisfied.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='2199'></a>Indeed, I never shall be satisfied
<br>With Romeo, till I behold him&mdash;dead&mdash;
<span class='playlinenum'>2200</span><br>Is my poor heart for a kinsman vex'd.
<br>Madam, if you could find out but a man
<br>To bear a poison, I would temper it;
<br>That Romeo should, upon receipt thereof,
<br>Soon sleep in quiet. O, how my heart abhors
<span class='playlinenum'>2205</span><br>To hear him named, and cannot come to him.
<br>To wreak the love I bore my cousin
<br>Upon his body that slaughter'd him!
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Lady Capulet. </strong><a name='2209'></a>Find thou the means, and I'll find such a man.
<br>But now I'll tell thee joyful tidings, girl.
<span class='playlinenum'>2210</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='2211'></a>And joy comes well in such a needy time:
<br>What are they, I beseech your ladyship?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Lady Capulet. </strong><a name='2213'></a>Well, well, thou hast a careful father, child;
<br>One who, to put thee from thy heaviness,
<br>Hath sorted out a sudden day of joy,
<span class='playlinenum'>2215</span><br>That thou expect'st not nor I look'd not for.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='2217'></a>Madam, in happy time, what day is that?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Lady Capulet. </strong><a name='2218'></a>Marry, my child, early next Thursday morn,
<br>The gallant, young and noble gentleman,
<br>The County Paris, at Saint Peter's Church,
<span class='playlinenum'>2220</span><br>Shall happily make thee there a joyful bride.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='2222'></a>Now, by Saint Peter's Church and Peter too,
<br>He shall not make me there a joyful bride.
<br>I wonder at this haste; that I must wed
<br>Ere he, that should be husband, comes to woo.
<span class='playlinenum'>2225</span><br>I pray you, tell my lord and father, madam,
<br>I will not marry yet; and, when I do, I swear,
<br>It shall be Romeo, whom you know I hate,
<br>Rather than Paris. These are news indeed!
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Lady Capulet. </strong><a name='2230'></a>Here comes your father; tell him so yourself,
<span class='playlinenum'>2230</span><br>And see how he will take it at your hands.
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='2232'></a>[Enter CAPULET and Nurse]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Capulet. </strong><a name='2233'></a>When the sun sets, the air doth drizzle dew;
<br>But for the sunset of my brother's son
<br>It rains downright.
<span class='playlinenum'>2235</span><br>How now! a conduit, girl? what, still in tears?
<br>Evermore showering? In one little body
<br>Thou counterfeit'st a bark, a sea, a wind;
<br>For still thy eyes, which I may call the sea,
<br>Do ebb and flow with tears; the bark thy body is,
<span class='playlinenum'>2240</span><br>Sailing in this salt flood; the winds, thy sighs;
<br>Who, raging with thy tears, and they with them,
<br>Without a sudden calm, will overset
<br>Thy tempest-tossed body. How now, wife!
<br>Have you deliver'd to her our decree?
<span class='playlinenum'>2245</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Lady Capulet. </strong><a name='2246'></a>Ay, sir; but she will none, she gives you thanks.
<br>I would the fool were married to her grave!
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Capulet. </strong><a name='2248'></a>Soft! take me with you, take me with you, wife.
<br>How! will she none? doth she not give us thanks?
<br>Is she not proud? doth she not count her blest,
<span class='playlinenum'>2250</span><br>Unworthy as she is, that we have wrought
<br>So worthy a gentleman to be her bridegroom?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='2253'></a>Not proud, you have; but thankful, that you have:
<br>Proud can I never be of what I hate;
<br>But thankful even for hate, that is meant love.
<span class='playlinenum'>2255</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Capulet. </strong><a name='2256'></a>How now, how now, chop-logic! What is this?
<br>'Proud,' and 'I thank you,' and 'I thank you not;'
<br>And yet 'not proud,' mistress minion, you,
<br>Thank me no thankings, nor, proud me no prouds,
<br>But fettle your fine joints 'gainst Thursday next,
<span class='playlinenum'>2260</span><br>To go with Paris to Saint Peter's Church,
<br>Or I will drag thee on a hurdle thither.
<br>Out, you green-sickness carrion! out, you baggage!
<br>You tallow-face!
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Lady Capulet. </strong><a name='2265'></a>Fie, fie! what, are you mad?
<span class='playlinenum'>2265</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='2266'></a>Good father, I beseech you on my knees,
<br>Hear me with patience but to speak a word.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Capulet. </strong><a name='2268'></a>Hang thee, young baggage! disobedient wretch!
<br>I tell thee what: get thee to church o' Thursday,
<br>Or never after look me in the face:
<span class='playlinenum'>2270</span><br>Speak not, reply not, do not answer me;
<br>My fingers itch. Wife, we scarce thought us blest
<br>That God had lent us but this only child;
<br>But now I see this one is one too much,
<br>And that we have a curse in having her:
<span class='playlinenum'>2275</span><br>Out on her, hilding!
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Nurse. </strong><a name='2277'></a>God in heaven bless her!
<br>You are to blame, my lord, to rate her so.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Capulet. </strong><a name='2279'></a>And why, my lady wisdom? hold your tongue,
<br>Good prudence; smatter with your gossips, go.
<span class='playlinenum'>2280</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Nurse. </strong><a name='2281'></a>I speak no treason.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Capulet. </strong><a name='2282'></a>O, God ye god-den.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Nurse. </strong><a name='2283'></a>May not one speak?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Capulet. </strong><a name='2284'></a>Peace, you mumbling fool!
<br>Utter your gravity o'er a gossip's bowl;
<span class='playlinenum'>2285</span><br>For here we need it not.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Lady Capulet. </strong><a name='2287'></a>You are too hot.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Capulet. </strong><a name='2288'></a>God's bread! it makes me mad:
<br>Day, night, hour, tide, time, work, play,
<br>Alone, in company, still my care hath been
<span class='playlinenum'>2290</span><br>To have her match'd: and having now provided
<br>A gentleman of noble parentage,
<br>Of fair demesnes, youthful, and nobly train'd,
<br>Stuff'd, as they say, with honourable parts,
<br>Proportion'd as one's thought would wish a man;
<span class='playlinenum'>2295</span><br>And then to have a wretched puling fool,
<br>A whining mammet, in her fortune's tender,
<br>To answer 'I'll not wed; I cannot love,
<br>I am too young; I pray you, pardon me.'
<br>But, as you will not wed, I'll pardon you:
<span class='playlinenum'>2300</span><br>Graze where you will you shall not house with me:
<br>Look to't, think on't, I do not use to jest.
<br>Thursday is near; lay hand on heart, advise:
<br>An you be mine, I'll give you to my friend;
<br>And you be not, hang, beg, starve, die in
<span class='playlinenum'>2305</span><br>the streets,
<br>For, by my soul, I'll ne'er acknowledge thee,
<br>Nor what is mine shall never do thee good:
<br>Trust to't, bethink you; I'll not be forsworn.
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='2310'></a>[Exit]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='2311'></a>Is there no pity sitting in the clouds,
<br>That sees into the bottom of my grief?
<br>O, sweet my mother, cast me not away!
<br>Delay this marriage for a month, a week;
<br>Or, if you do not, make the bridal bed
<span class='playlinenum'>2315</span><br>In that dim monument where Tybalt lies.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Lady Capulet. </strong><a name='2317'></a>Talk not to me, for I'll not speak a word:
<br>Do as thou wilt, for I have done with thee.
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='2319'></a>[Exit]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='2320'></a>O God!&mdash;O nurse, how shall this be prevented?
<span class='playlinenum'>2320</span><br>My husband is on earth, my faith in heaven;
<br>How shall that faith return again to earth,
<br>Unless that husband send it me from heaven
<br>By leaving earth? comfort me, counsel me.
<br>Alack, alack, that heaven should practise stratagems
<span class='playlinenum'>2325</span><br>Upon so soft a subject as myself!
<br>What say'st thou? hast thou not a word of joy?
<br>Some comfort, nurse.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Nurse. </strong><a name='2329'></a>Faith, here it is.
<br>Romeo is banish'd; and all the world to nothing,
<span class='playlinenum'>2330</span><br>That he dares ne'er come back to challenge you;
<br>Or, if he do, it needs must be by stealth.
<br>Then, since the case so stands as now it doth,
<br>I think it best you married with the county.
<br>O, he's a lovely gentleman!
<span class='playlinenum'>2335</span><br>Romeo's a dishclout to him: an eagle, madam,
<br>Hath not so green, so quick, so fair an eye
<br>As Paris hath. Beshrew my very heart,
<br>I think you are happy in this second match,
<br>For it excels your first: or if it did not,
<span class='playlinenum'>2340</span><br>Your first is dead; or 'twere as good he were,
<br>As living here and you no use of him.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='2343'></a>Speakest thou from thy heart?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Nurse. </strong><a name='2344'></a>And from my soul too;
<br>Or else beshrew them both.
<span class='playlinenum'>2345</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='2346'></a>Amen!
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Nurse. </strong><a name='2347'></a>What?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='2348'></a>Well, thou hast comforted me marvellous much.
<br>Go in: and tell my lady I am gone,
<br>Having displeased my father, to Laurence' cell,
<span class='playlinenum'>2350</span><br>To make confession and to be absolved.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Nurse. </strong><a name='2352'></a>Marry, I will; and this is wisely done.
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='2353'></a>[Exit]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='2354'></a>Ancient damnation! O most wicked fiend!
<br>Is it more sin to wish me thus forsworn,
<span class='playlinenum'>2355</span><br>Or to dispraise my lord with that same tongue
<br>Which she hath praised him with above compare
<br>So many thousand times? Go, counsellor;
<br>Thou and my bosom henceforth shall be twain.
<br>I'll to the friar, to know his remedy:
<span class='playlinenum'>2360</span><br>If all else fail, myself have power to die.
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='2362'></a>[Exit]
</li></ul>

<span class='playlinenum'>2365</span><br>And I am nothing slow to slack his haste.

<span class='playlinenum'>2375</span><br>Which, too much minded by herself alone,

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='2381'></a>[Enter JULIET]

</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='2385'></a>What must be shall be.

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Friar Laurence. </strong><a name='2412'></a>Ah, Juliet, I already know thy grief;
<br>It strains me past the compass of my wits:
<br>I hear thou must, and nothing may prorogue it,
<br>On Thursday next be married to this county.
<span class='playlinenum'>2415</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='2416'></a>Tell me not, friar, that thou hear'st of this,
<br>Unless thou tell me how I may prevent it:
<br>If, in thy wisdom, thou canst give no help,
<br>Do thou but call my resolution wise,
<br>And with this knife I'll help it presently.
<span class='playlinenum'>2420</span><br>God join'd my heart and Romeo's, thou our hands;
<br>And ere this hand, by thee to Romeo seal'd,
<br>Shall be the label to another deed,
<br>Or my true heart with treacherous revolt
<br>Turn to another, this shall slay them both:
<span class='playlinenum'>2425</span><br>Therefore, out of thy long-experienced time,
<br>Give me some present counsel, or, behold,
<br>'Twixt my extremes and me this bloody knife
<br>Shall play the umpire, arbitrating that
<br>Which the commission of thy years and art
<span class='playlinenum'>2430</span><br>Could to no issue of true honour bring.
<br>Be not so long to speak; I long to die,
<br>If what thou speak'st speak not of remedy.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Friar Laurence. </strong><a name='2434'></a>Hold, daughter: I do spy a kind of hope,
<br>Which craves as desperate an execution.
<span class='playlinenum'>2435</span><br>As that is desperate which we would prevent.
<br>If, rather than to marry County Paris,
<br>Thou hast the strength of will to slay thyself,
<br>Then is it likely thou wilt undertake
<br>A thing like death to chide away this shame,
<span class='playlinenum'>2440</span><br>That copest with death himself to scape from it:
<br>And, if thou darest, I'll give thee remedy.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='2443'></a>O, bid me leap, rather than marry Paris,
<br>From off the battlements of yonder tower;
<br>Or walk in thievish ways; or bid me lurk
<span class='playlinenum'>2445</span><br>Where serpents are; chain me with roaring bears;
<br>Or shut me nightly in a charnel-house,
<br>O'er-cover'd quite with dead men's rattling bones,
<br>With reeky shanks and yellow chapless skulls;
<br>Or bid me go into a new-made grave
<span class='playlinenum'>2450</span><br>And hide me with a dead man in his shroud;
<br>Things that, to hear them told, have made me tremble;
<br>And I will do it without fear or doubt,
<br>To live an unstain'd wife to my sweet love.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Friar Laurence. </strong><a name='2455'></a>Hold, then; go home, be merry, give consent
<span class='playlinenum'>2455</span><br>To marry Paris: Wednesday is to-morrow:
<br>To-morrow night look that thou lie alone;
<br>Let not thy nurse lie with thee in thy chamber:
<br>Take thou this vial, being then in bed,
<br>And this distilled liquor drink thou off;
<span class='playlinenum'>2460</span><br>When presently through all thy veins shall run
<br>A cold and drowsy humour, for no pulse
<br>Shall keep his native progress, but surcease:
<br>No warmth, no breath, shall testify thou livest;
<br>The roses in thy lips and cheeks shall fade
<span class='playlinenum'>2465</span><br>To paly ashes, thy eyes' windows fall,
<br>Like death, when he shuts up the day of life;
<br>Each part, deprived of supple government,
<br>Shall, stiff and stark and cold, appear like death:
<br>And in this borrow'd likeness of shrunk death
<span class='playlinenum'>2470</span><br>Thou shalt continue two and forty hours,
<br>And then awake as from a pleasant sleep.
<br>Now, when the bridegroom in the morning comes
<br>To rouse thee from thy bed, there art thou dead:
<br>Then, as the manner of our country is,
<span class='playlinenum'>2475</span><br>In thy best robes uncover'd on the bier

<br>Shall Romeo by my letters know our drift,
<span class='playlinenum'>2480</span><br>And hither shall he come: and he and I

<br>And this shall free thee from this present shame;
<br>If no inconstant toy, nor womanish fear,
<span class='playlinenum'>2485</span><br>Abate thy valour in the acting it.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='2487'></a>Give me, give me! O, tell not me of fear!
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Friar Laurence. </strong><a name='2488'></a>Hold; get you gone, be strong and prosperous
<br>In this resolve: I'll send a friar with speed
<br>To Mantua, with my letters to thy lord.
<span class='playlinenum'>2490</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='2491'></a>Love give me strength! and strength shall help afford.
<br>Farewell, dear father!
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='2493'></a>[Exeunt]

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='2627'></a>[Exeunt LADY CAPULET and Nurse]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Capulet. </strong><a name='2628'></a>A jealous hood, a jealous hood!
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='2629'></a>[Enter three or four Servingmen, with spits, logs, and baskets]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Capulet. </strong><a name='2630'></a>Now, fellow,
<span class='playlinenum'>2630</span><br>What's there?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>First Servant. </strong><a name='2632'></a>Things for the cook, sir; but I know not what.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Capulet. </strong><a name='2633'></a>Make haste, make haste.
<br><i>[Exit First Servant]</i>
<br>Sirrah, fetch drier logs:
<span class='playlinenum'>2635</span><br>Call Peter, he will show thee where they are.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Second Servant. </strong><a name='2637'></a>I have a head, sir, that will find out logs,
<br>And never trouble Peter for the matter.
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='2639'></a>[Exit]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Capulet. </strong><a name='2640'></a>Mass, and well said; a merry whoreson, ha!
<span class='playlinenum'>2640</span><br>Thou shalt be logger-head. Good faith, 'tis day:
<br>The county will be here with music straight,
<br>For so he said he would: I hear him near.
<br><i>[Music within]</i>
<br>Nurse! Wife! What, ho! What, nurse, I say!
<span class='playlinenum'>2645</span><br><i>[Re-enter Nurse]</i>
<br>Go waken Juliet, go and trim her up;
<br>I'll go and chat with Paris: hie, make haste,
<br>Make haste; the bridegroom he is come already:
<br>Make haste, I say.
<span class='playlinenum'>2650</span></li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='2651'></a>[Exeunt]

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Lady Capulet. </strong><a name='2702'></a>Accursed, unhappy, wretched, hateful day!

<br>But one, poor one, one poor and loving child,
<span class='playlinenum'>2705</span><br>But one thing to rejoice and solace in,
<br>And cruel death hath catch'd it from my sight!
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Nurse. </strong><a name='2708'></a>O woe! O woful, woful, woful day!

<br>That ever, ever, I did yet behold!
<span class='playlinenum'>2710</span><br>O day! O day! O day! O hateful day!
<br>Never was seen so black a day as this:
<br>O woful day, O woful day!
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Paris. </strong><a name='2714'></a>Beguiled, divorced, wronged, spited, slain!

<span class='playlinenum'>2715</span><br>By cruel cruel thee quite overthrown!
<br>O love! O life! not life, but love in death!
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Capulet. </strong><a name='2718'></a>Despised, distressed, hated, martyr'd, kill'd!

<br>To murder, murder our solemnity?
<span class='playlinenum'>2720</span><br>O child! O child! my soul, and not my child!
<br>Dead art thou! Alack! my child is dead;
<br>And with my child my joys are buried.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Friar Laurence. </strong><a name='2724'></a>Peace, ho, for shame! confusion's cure lives not
<br>In these confusions. Heaven and yourself
<span class='playlinenum'>2725</span><br>Had part in this fair maid; now heaven hath all,
<br>And all the better is it for the maid:
<br>Your part in her you could not keep from death,
<br>But heaven keeps his part in eternal life.
<br>The most you sought was her promotion;
<span class='playlinenum'>2730</span><br>For 'twas your heaven she should be advanced:
<br>And weep ye now, seeing she is advanced
<br>Above the clouds, as high as heaven itself?
<br>O, in this love, you love your child so ill,
<br>That you run mad, seeing that she is well:
<span class='playlinenum'>2735</span><br>She's not well married that lives married long;
<br>But she's best married that dies married young.
<br>Dry up your tears, and stick your rosemary
<br>On this fair corse; and, as the custom is,
<br>In all her best array bear her to church:
<span class='playlinenum'>2740</span><br>For though fond nature bids us an lament,

<br>Our solemn hymns to sullen dirges change,
<br>Our bridal flowers serve for a buried corse,
<br>And all things change them to the contrary.

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Friar Laurence. </strong><a name='2750'></a>Sir, go you in; and, madam, go with him;
<span class='playlinenum'>2750</span><br>And go, Sir Paris; every one prepare
<br>To follow this fair corse unto her grave:
<br>The heavens do lour upon you for some ill;
<br>Move them no more by crossing their high will.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Nurse. </strong><a name='2757'></a>Honest goodfellows, ah, put up, put up;

</li></ul>

<span class='playlinenum'>2770</span></li></ul>

</li></ul>

</li></ul>

<span class='playlinenum'>2775</span></li></ul>

<br>'When griping grief the heart doth wound,
<br>And doleful dumps the mind oppress,
<span class='playlinenum'>2785</span><br>Then music with her silver sound'&mdash;

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Third Musician. </strong><a name='2793'></a>Faith, I know not what to say.

</li></ul>

<span class='playlinenum'>2800</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Second Musician. </strong><a name='2801'></a>Hang him, Jack! Come, we'll in here; tarry for the

</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='2803'></a>[Exeunt]

<td></li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='2804'></a>[Enter ROMEO]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='2805'></a>If I may trust the flattering truth of sleep,
<span class='playlinenum'>2805</span><br>My dreams presage some joyful news at hand:
<br>My bosom's lord sits lightly in his throne;
<br>And all this day an unaccustom'd spirit
<br>Lifts me above the ground with cheerful thoughts.
<br>I dreamt my lady came and found me dead&mdash;
<span class='playlinenum'>2810</span><br>Strange dream, that gives a dead man leave
<br>to think!&mdash;
<br>And breathed such life with kisses in my lips,
<br>That I revived, and was an emperor.
<br>Ah me! how sweet is love itself possess'd,
<span class='playlinenum'>2815</span><br>When but love's shadows are so rich in joy!
<br><i>[Enter BALTHASAR, booted]</i>
<br>News from Verona!&mdash;How now, Balthasar!
<br>Dost thou not bring me letters from the friar?
<br>How doth my lady? Is my father well?
<span class='playlinenum'>2820</span><br>How fares my Juliet? that I ask again;
<br>For nothing can be ill, if she be well.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Balthasar. </strong><a name='2823'></a>Then she is well, and nothing can be ill:
<br>Her body sleeps in Capel's monument,
<br>And her immortal part with angels lives.
<span class='playlinenum'>2825</span><br>I saw her laid low in her kindred's vault,
<br>And presently took post to tell it you:
<br>O, pardon me for bringing these ill news,
<br>Since you did leave it for my office, sir.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='2830'></a>Is it even so? then I defy you, stars!
<span class='playlinenum'>2830</span><br>Thou know'st my lodging: get me ink and paper,
<br>And hire post-horses; I will hence to-night.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Balthasar. </strong><a name='2833'></a>I do beseech you, sir, have patience:
<br>Your looks are pale and wild, and do import
<br>Some misadventure.
<span class='playlinenum'>2835</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='2836'></a>Tush, thou art deceived:
<br>Leave me, and do the thing I bid thee do.
<br>Hast thou no letters to me from the friar?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Balthasar. </strong><a name='2839'></a>No, my good lord.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='2840'></a>No matter: get thee gone,
<span class='playlinenum'>2840</span><br>And hire those horses; I'll be with thee straight.
<br><i>[Exit BALTHASAR]</i>
<br>Well, Juliet, I will lie with thee to-night.
<br>Let's see for means: O mischief, thou art swift
<br>To enter in the thoughts of desperate men!
<span class='playlinenum'>2845</span><br>I do remember an apothecary,&mdash;
<br>And hereabouts he dwells,&mdash;which late I noted
<br>In tatter'd weeds, with overwhelming brows,
<br>Culling of simples; meagre were his looks,
<br>Sharp misery had worn him to the bones:
<span class='playlinenum'>2850</span><br>And in his needy shop a tortoise hung,
<br>An alligator stuff'd, and other skins
<br>Of ill-shaped fishes; and about his shelves
<br>A beggarly account of empty boxes,
<br>Green earthen pots, bladders and musty seeds,
<span class='playlinenum'>2855</span><br>Remnants of packthread and old cakes of roses,
<br>Were thinly scatter'd, to make up a show.
<br>Noting this penury, to myself I said
<br>'An if a man did need a poison now,
<br>Whose sale is present death in Mantua,
<span class='playlinenum'>2860</span><br>Here lives a caitiff wretch would sell it him.'
<br>O, this same thought did but forerun my need;
<br>And this same needy man must sell it me.
<br>As I remember, this should be the house.
<br>Being holiday, the beggar's shop is shut.
<span class='playlinenum'>2865</span><br>What, ho! apothecary!
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='2867'></a>[Enter Apothecary]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Apothecary. </strong><a name='2868'></a>Who calls so loud?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='2869'></a>Come hither, man. I see that thou art poor:
<br>Hold, there is forty ducats: let me have
<span class='playlinenum'>2870</span><br>A dram of poison, such soon-speeding gear
<br>As will disperse itself through all the veins
<br>That the life-weary taker may fall dead
<br>And that the trunk may be discharged of breath
<br>As violently as hasty powder fired
<span class='playlinenum'>2875</span><br>Doth hurry from the fatal cannon's womb.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Apothecary. </strong><a name='2877'></a>Such mortal drugs I have; but Mantua's law
<br>Is death to any he that utters them.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='2879'></a>Art thou so bare and full of wretchedness,
<br>And fear'st to die? famine is in thy cheeks,
<span class='playlinenum'>2880</span><br>Need and oppression starveth in thine eyes,
<br>Contempt and beggary hangs upon thy back;
<br>The world is not thy friend nor the world's law;
<br>The world affords no law to make thee rich;
<br>Then be not poor, but break it, and take this.
<span class='playlinenum'>2885</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Apothecary. </strong><a name='2886'></a>My poverty, but not my will, consents.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='2887'></a>I pay thy poverty, and not thy will.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Apothecary. </strong><a name='2888'></a>Put this in any liquid thing you will,
<br>And drink it off; and, if you had the strength
<br>Of twenty men, it would dispatch you straight.
<span class='playlinenum'>2890</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='2891'></a>There is thy gold, worse poison to men's souls,
<br>Doing more murders in this loathsome world,
<br>Than these poor compounds that thou mayst not sell.
<br>I sell thee poison; thou hast sold me none.
<br>Farewell: buy food, and get thyself in flesh.
<span class='playlinenum'>2895</span><br>Come, cordial and not poison, go with me
<br>To Juliet's grave; for there must I use thee.
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='2898'></a>[Exeunt]
</li></ul>
