<td></li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='2899'></a>[Enter FRIAR JOHN]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Friar John. </strong><a name='2900'></a>Holy Franciscan friar! brother, ho!
<span class='playlinenum'>2900</span></li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='2901'></a>[Enter FRIAR LAURENCE]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Friar Laurence. </strong><a name='2902'></a>This same should be the voice of Friar John.
<br>Welcome from Mantua: what says Romeo?
<br>Or, if his mind be writ, give me his letter.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Friar John. </strong><a name='2905'></a>Going to find a bare-foot brother out
<span class='playlinenum'>2905</span><br>One of our order, to associate me,
<br>Here in this city visiting the sick,
<br>And finding him, the searchers of the town,
<br>Suspecting that we both were in a house
<br>Where the infectious pestilence did reign,
<span class='playlinenum'>2910</span><br>Seal'd up the doors, and would not let us forth;
<br>So that my speed to Mantua there was stay'd.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Friar Laurence. </strong><a name='2913'></a>Who bare my letter, then, to Romeo?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Friar John. </strong><a name='2914'></a>I could not send it,&mdash;here it is again,&mdash;
<br>Nor get a messenger to bring it thee,
<span class='playlinenum'>2915</span><br>So fearful were they of infection.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Friar Laurence. </strong><a name='2917'></a>Unhappy fortune! by my brotherhood,
<br>The letter was not nice but full of charge
<br>Of dear import, and the neglecting it
<br>May do much danger. Friar John, go hence;
<span class='playlinenum'>2920</span><br>Get me an iron crow, and bring it straight
<br>Unto my cell.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Friar John. </strong><a name='2923'></a>Brother, I'll go and bring it thee.
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='2924'></a>[Exit]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Friar Laurence. </strong><a name='2925'></a>Now must I to the monument alone;
<span class='playlinenum'>2925</span><br>Within three hours will fair Juliet wake:
<br>She will beshrew me much that Romeo
<br>Hath had no notice of these accidents;
<br>But I will write again to Mantua,
<br>And keep her at my cell till Romeo come;
<span class='playlinenum'>2930</span><br>Poor living corse, closed in a dead man's tomb!
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='2932'></a>[Exit]
</li></ul>

<table width='600' cellspacing='30'>
<tr>
<td></li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='2933'></a>[Enter PARIS, and his Page bearing flowers and a torch]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Paris. </strong><a name='2934'></a>Give me thy torch, boy: hence, and stand aloof:
<br>Yet put it out, for I would not be seen.
<span class='playlinenum'>2935</span><br>Under yond yew-trees lay thee all along,
<br>Holding thine ear close to the hollow ground;
<br>So shall no foot upon the churchyard tread,
<br>Being loose, unfirm, with digging up of graves,
<br>But thou shalt hear it: whistle then to me,
<span class='playlinenum'>2940</span><br>As signal that thou hear'st something approach.
<br>Give me those flowers. Do as I bid thee, go.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Page. </strong><a name='2943'></a><i>[Aside]</i> I am almost afraid to stand alone
<br>Here in the churchyard; yet I will adventure.
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='2945'></a>[Retires]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Paris. </strong><a name='2946'></a>Sweet flower, with flowers thy bridal bed I strew,&mdash;
<br>O woe! thy canopy is dust and stones;&mdash;
<br>Which with sweet water nightly I will dew,
<br>Or, wanting that, with tears distill'd by moans:
<br>The obsequies that I for thee will keep
<span class='playlinenum'>2950</span><br>Nightly shall be to strew thy grave and weep.
<br><i>[The Page whistles]</i>
<br>The boy gives warning something doth approach.
<br>What cursed foot wanders this way to-night,
<br>To cross my obsequies and true love's rite?
<span class='playlinenum'>2955</span><br>What with a torch! muffle me, night, awhile.
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='2957'></a>[Retires]
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='2958'></a>[Enter ROMEO and BALTHASAR, with a torch, mattock, &c]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='2959'></a>Give me that mattock and the wrenching iron.
<br>Hold, take this letter; early in the morning
<span class='playlinenum'>2960</span><br>See thou deliver it to my lord and father.
<br>Give me the light: upon thy life, I charge thee,
<br>Whate'er thou hear'st or seest, stand all aloof,
<br>And do not interrupt me in my course.
<br>Why I descend into this bed of death,
<span class='playlinenum'>2965</span><br>Is partly to behold my lady's face;
<br>But chiefly to take thence from her dead finger
<br>A precious ring, a ring that I must use
<br>In dear employment: therefore hence, be gone:
<br>But if thou, jealous, dost return to pry
<span class='playlinenum'>2970</span><br>In what I further shall intend to do,
<br>By heaven, I will tear thee joint by joint
<br>And strew this hungry churchyard with thy limbs:
<br>The time and my intents are savage-wild,
<br>More fierce and more inexorable far
<span class='playlinenum'>2975</span><br>Than empty tigers or the roaring sea.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Balthasar. </strong><a name='2977'></a>I will be gone, sir, and not trouble you.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='2978'></a>So shalt thou show me friendship. Take thou that:
<br>Live, and be prosperous: and farewell, good fellow.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Balthasar. </strong><a name='2980'></a><i>[Aside]</i> For all this same, I'll hide me hereabout:
<span class='playlinenum'>2980</span><br>His looks I fear, and his intents I doubt.
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='2982'></a>[Retires]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='2983'></a>Thou detestable maw, thou womb of death,
<br>Gorged with the dearest morsel of the earth,
<br>Thus I enforce thy rotten jaws to open,
<span class='playlinenum'>2985</span><br>And, in despite, I'll cram thee with more food!
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='2987'></a>[Opens the tomb]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Paris. </strong><a name='2988'></a>This is that banish'd haughty Montague,
<br>That murder'd my love's cousin, with which grief,
<br>It is supposed, the fair creature died;
<span class='playlinenum'>2990</span><br>And here is come to do some villanous shame
<br>To the dead bodies: I will apprehend him.
<br><i>[Comes forward]</i>
<br>Stop thy unhallow'd toil, vile Montague!
<br>Can vengeance be pursued further than death?
<span class='playlinenum'>2995</span><br>Condemned villain, I do apprehend thee:
<br>Obey, and go with me; for thou must die.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='2998'></a>I must indeed; and therefore came I hither.
<br>Good gentle youth, tempt not a desperate man;
<br>Fly hence, and leave me: think upon these gone;
<span class='playlinenum'>3000</span><br>Let them affright thee. I beseech thee, youth,
<br>Put not another sin upon my head,
<br>By urging me to fury: O, be gone!
<br>By heaven, I love thee better than myself;
<br>For I come hither arm'd against myself:
<span class='playlinenum'>3005</span><br>Stay not, be gone; live, and hereafter say,
<br>A madman's mercy bade thee run away.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Paris. </strong><a name='3008'></a>I do defy thy conjurations,
<br>And apprehend thee for a felon here.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='3010'></a>Wilt thou provoke me? then have at thee, boy!
<span class='playlinenum'>3010</span></li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='3011'></a>[They fight]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Page. </strong><a name='3012'></a>O Lord, they fight! I will go call the watch.
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='3013'></a>[Exit]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Paris. </strong><a name='3014'></a>O, I am slain!
<br><i>[Falls]</i>
<span class='playlinenum'>3015</span><br>If thou be merciful,
<br>Open the tomb, lay me with Juliet.
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='3018'></a>[Dies]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Romeo. </strong><a name='3019'></a>In faith, I will. Let me peruse this face.
<br>Mercutio's kinsman, noble County Paris!
<span class='playlinenum'>3020</span><br>What said my man, when my betossed soul
<br>Did not attend him as we rode? I think
<br>He told me Paris should have married Juliet:
<br>Said he not so? or did I dream it so?
<br>Or am I mad, hearing him talk of Juliet,
<span class='playlinenum'>3025</span><br>To think it was so? O, give me thy hand,
<br>One writ with me in sour misfortune's book!
<br>I'll bury thee in a triumphant grave;
<br>A grave? O no! a lantern, slaughter'd youth,
<br>For here lies Juliet, and her beauty makes
<span class='playlinenum'>3030</span><br>This vault a feasting presence full of light.
<br>Death, lie thou there, by a dead man interr'd.
<br><i>[Laying PARIS in the tomb]</i>
<br>How oft when men are at the point of death
<br>Have they been merry! which their keepers call
<span class='playlinenum'>3035</span><br>A lightning before death: O, how may I
<br>Call this a lightning? O my love! my wife!
<br>Death, that hath suck'd the honey of thy breath,
<br>Hath had no power yet upon thy beauty:
<br>Thou art not conquer'd; beauty's ensign yet
<span class='playlinenum'>3040</span><br>Is crimson in thy lips and in thy cheeks,
<br>And death's pale flag is not advanced there.
<br>Tybalt, liest thou there in thy bloody sheet?
<br>O, what more favour can I do to thee,
<br>Than with that hand that cut thy youth in twain
<span class='playlinenum'>3045</span><br>To sunder his that was thine enemy?
<br>Forgive me, cousin! Ah, dear Juliet,
<br>Why art thou yet so fair? shall I believe
<br>That unsubstantial death is amorous,
<br>And that the lean abhorred monster keeps
<span class='playlinenum'>3050</span><br>Thee here in dark to be his paramour?
<br>For fear of that, I still will stay with thee;
<br>And never from this palace of dim night
<br>Depart again: here, here will I remain
<br>With worms that are thy chamber-maids; O, here
<span class='playlinenum'>3055</span><br>Will I set up my everlasting rest,
<br>And shake the yoke of inauspicious stars
<br>From this world-wearied flesh. Eyes, look your last!
<br>Arms, take your last embrace! and, lips, O you
<br>The doors of breath, seal with a righteous kiss
<span class='playlinenum'>3060</span><br>A dateless bargain to engrossing death!
<br>Come, bitter conduct, come, unsavoury guide!
<br>Thou desperate pilot, now at once run on
<br>The dashing rocks thy sea-sick weary bark!
<br>Here's to my love!
<span class='playlinenum'>3065</span><br><i>[Drinks]</i>
<br>O true apothecary!
<br>Thy drugs are quick. Thus with a kiss I die.
<br><i>[Dies]</i>
<br><i>[Enter, at the other end of the churchyard, FRIAR]</i>
<span class='playlinenum'>3070</span><br>LAURENCE, with a lantern, crow, and spade]</i>
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Friar Laurence. </strong><a name='3072'></a>Saint Francis be my speed! how oft to-night
<br>Have my old feet stumbled at graves! Who's there?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Balthasar. </strong><a name='3074'></a>Here's one, a friend, and one that knows you well.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Friar Laurence. </strong><a name='3075'></a>Bliss be upon you! Tell me, good my friend,
<span class='playlinenum'>3075</span><br>What torch is yond, that vainly lends his light
<br>To grubs and eyeless skulls? as I discern,
<br>It burneth in the Capel's monument.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Balthasar. </strong><a name='3079'></a>It doth so, holy sir; and there's my master,
<br>One that you love.
<span class='playlinenum'>3080</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Friar Laurence. </strong><a name='3081'></a>Who is it?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Balthasar. </strong><a name='3082'></a>Romeo.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Friar Laurence. </strong><a name='3083'></a>How long hath he been there?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Balthasar. </strong><a name='3084'></a>Full half an hour.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Friar Laurence. </strong><a name='3085'></a>Go with me to the vault.
<span class='playlinenum'>3085</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Balthasar. </strong><a name='3086'></a>I dare not, sir
<br>My master knows not but I am gone hence;
<br>And fearfully did menace me with death,
<br>If I did stay to look on his intents.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Friar Laurence. </strong><a name='3090'></a>Stay, then; I'll go alone. Fear comes upon me:
<span class='playlinenum'>3090</span><br>O, much I fear some ill unlucky thing.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Balthasar. </strong><a name='3092'></a>As I did sleep under this yew-tree here,
<br>I dreamt my master and another fought,
<br>And that my master slew him.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Friar Laurence. </strong><a name='3095'></a>Romeo!
<span class='playlinenum'>3095</span><br><i>[Advances]</i>
<br>Alack, alack, what blood is this, which stains
<br>The stony entrance of this sepulchre?
<br>What mean these masterless and gory swords
<br>To lie discolour'd by this place of peace?
<span class='playlinenum'>3100</span><br><i>[Enters the tomb]</i>
<br>Romeo! O, pale! Who else? what, Paris too?
<br>And steep'd in blood? Ah, what an unkind hour
<br>Is guilty of this lamentable chance!
<br>The lady stirs.
<span class='playlinenum'>3105</span></li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='3106'></a>[JULIET wakes]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='3107'></a>O comfortable friar! where is my lord?
<br>I do remember well where I should be,
<br>And there I am. Where is my Romeo?
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='3110'></a>[Noise within]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Friar Laurence. </strong><a name='3111'></a>I hear some noise. Lady, come from that nest
<br>Of death, contagion, and unnatural sleep:
<br>A greater power than we can contradict
<br>Hath thwarted our intents. Come, come away.
<br>Thy husband in thy bosom there lies dead;
<span class='playlinenum'>3115</span><br>And Paris too. Come, I'll dispose of thee
<br>Among a sisterhood of holy nuns:
<br>Stay not to question, for the watch is coming;
<br>Come, go, good Juliet,
<br><i>[Noise again]</i>
<span class='playlinenum'>3120</span><br>I dare no longer stay.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='3122'></a>Go, get thee hence, for I will not away.
<br><i>[Exit FRIAR LAURENCE]</i>
<br>What's here? a cup, closed in my true love's hand?
<br>Poison, I see, hath been his timeless end:
<span class='playlinenum'>3125</span><br>O churl! drunk all, and left no friendly drop
<br>To help me after? I will kiss thy lips;
<br>Haply some poison yet doth hang on them,
<br>To make die with a restorative.
<br><i>[Kisses him]</i>
<span class='playlinenum'>3130</span><br>Thy lips are warm.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>First Watchman. </strong><a name='3132'></a><i>[Within]</i> Lead, boy: which way?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Juliet. </strong><a name='3133'></a>Yea, noise? then I'll be brief. O happy dagger!
<br><i>[Snatching ROMEO's dagger]</i>
<br>This is thy sheath;
<span class='playlinenum'>3135</span><br><i>[Stabs herself]</i>
<br>there rust, and let me die.
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='3138'></a>[Falls on ROMEO's body, and dies]
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='3139'></a>[Enter Watch, with the Page of PARIS]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Page. </strong><a name='3140'></a>This is the place; there, where the torch doth burn.
<span class='playlinenum'>3140</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>First Watchman. </strong><a name='3141'></a>The ground is bloody; search about the churchyard:
<br>Go, some of you, whoe'er you find attach.
<br>Pitiful sight! here lies the county slain,
<br>And Juliet bleeding, warm, and newly dead,
<br>Who here hath lain these two days buried.
<span class='playlinenum'>3145</span><br>Go, tell the prince: run to the Capulets:
<br>Raise up the Montagues: some others search:
<br>We see the ground whereon these woes do lie;
<br>But the true ground of all these piteous woes
<br>We cannot without circumstance descry.
<span class='playlinenum'>3150</span></li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='3151'></a>[Re-enter some of the Watch, with BALTHASAR]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Second Watchman. </strong><a name='3152'></a>Here's Romeo's man; we found him in the churchyard.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>First Watchman. </strong><a name='3153'></a>Hold him in safety, till the prince come hither.
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='3154'></a>[Re-enter others of the Watch, with FRIAR LAURENCE]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Third Watchman. </strong><a name='3155'></a>Here is a friar, that trembles, sighs and weeps:
<span class='playlinenum'>3155</span><br>We took this mattock and this spade from him,
<br>As he was coming from this churchyard side.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>First Watchman. </strong><a name='3158'></a>A great suspicion: stay the friar too.
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='3159'></a>[Enter the PRINCE and Attendants]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Prince Escalus. </strong><a name='3160'></a>What misadventure is so early up,
<span class='playlinenum'>3160</span><br>That calls our person from our morning's rest?
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='3162'></a>[Enter CAPULET, LADY CAPULET, and others]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Capulet. </strong><a name='3163'></a>What should it be, that they so shriek abroad?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Lady Capulet. </strong><a name='3164'></a>The people in the street cry Romeo,
<br>Some Juliet, and some Paris; and all run,
<span class='playlinenum'>3165</span><br>With open outcry toward our monument.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Prince Escalus. </strong><a name='3167'></a>What fear is this which startles in our ears?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>First Watchman. </strong><a name='3168'></a>Sovereign, here lies the County Paris slain;
<br>And Romeo dead; and Juliet, dead before,
<br>Warm and new kill'd.
<span class='playlinenum'>3170</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Prince Escalus. </strong><a name='3171'></a>Search, seek, and know how this foul murder comes.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>First Watchman. </strong><a name='3172'></a>Here is a friar, and slaughter'd Romeo's man;
<br>With instruments upon them, fit to open
<br>These dead men's tombs.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Capulet. </strong><a name='3175'></a>O heavens! O wife, look how our daughter bleeds!
<span class='playlinenum'>3175</span><br>This dagger hath mista'en&mdash;for, lo, his house
<br>Is empty on the back of Montague,&mdash;
<br>And it mis-sheathed in my daughter's bosom!
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Lady Capulet. </strong><a name='3179'></a>O me! this sight of death is as a bell,
<br>That warns my old age to a sepulchre.
<span class='playlinenum'>3180</span></li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='3181'></a>[Enter MONTAGUE and others]
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Prince Escalus. </strong><a name='3182'></a>Come, Montague; for thou art early up,
<br>To see thy son and heir more early down.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Montague. </strong><a name='3184'></a>Alas, my liege, my wife is dead to-night;
<br>Grief of my son's exile hath stopp'd her breath:
<span class='playlinenum'>3185</span><br>What further woe conspires against mine age?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Prince Escalus. </strong><a name='3187'></a>Look, and thou shalt see.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Montague. </strong><a name='3188'></a>O thou untaught! what manners is in this?
<br>To press before thy father to a grave?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Prince Escalus. </strong><a name='3190'></a>Seal up the mouth of outrage for a while,
<span class='playlinenum'>3190</span><br>Till we can clear these ambiguities,
<br>And know their spring, their head, their
<br>true descent;
<br>And then will I be general of your woes,
<br>And lead you even to death: meantime forbear,
<span class='playlinenum'>3195</span><br>And let mischance be slave to patience.
<br>Bring forth the parties of suspicion.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Friar Laurence. </strong><a name='3198'></a>I am the greatest, able to do least,
<br>Yet most suspected, as the time and place
<br>Doth make against me of this direful murder;
<span class='playlinenum'>3200</span><br>And here I stand, both to impeach and purge
<br>Myself condemned and myself excused.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Prince Escalus. </strong><a name='3203'></a>Then say at once what thou dost know in this.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Friar Laurence. </strong><a name='3204'></a>I will be brief, for my short date of breath
<br>Is not so long as is a tedious tale.
<span class='playlinenum'>3205</span><br>Romeo, there dead, was husband to that Juliet;
<br>And she, there dead, that Romeo's faithful wife:
<br>I married them; and their stol'n marriage-day
<br>Was Tybalt's dooms-day, whose untimely death
<br>Banish'd the new-made bridegroom from the city,
<span class='playlinenum'>3210</span><br>For whom, and not for Tybalt, Juliet pined.
<br>You, to remove that siege of grief from her,
<br>Betroth'd and would have married her perforce
<br>To County Paris: then comes she to me,
<br>And, with wild looks, bid me devise some mean
<span class='playlinenum'>3215</span><br>To rid her from this second marriage,
<br>Or in my cell there would she kill herself.
<br>Then gave I her, so tutor'd by my art,
<br>A sleeping potion; which so took effect
<br>As I intended, for it wrought on her
<span class='playlinenum'>3220</span><br>The form of death: meantime I writ to Romeo,
<br>That he should hither come as this dire night,
<br>To help to take her from her borrow'd grave,
<br>Being the time the potion's force should cease.
<br>But he which bore my letter, Friar John,
<span class='playlinenum'>3225</span><br>Was stay'd by accident, and yesternight
<br>Return'd my letter back. Then all alone
<br>At the prefixed hour of her waking,
<br>Came I to take her from her kindred's vault;
<br>Meaning to keep her closely at my cell,
<span class='playlinenum'>3230</span><br>Till I conveniently could send to Romeo:
<br>But when I came, some minute ere the time
<br>Of her awaking, here untimely lay
<br>The noble Paris and true Romeo dead.
<br>She wakes; and I entreated her come forth,
<span class='playlinenum'>3235</span><br>And bear this work of heaven with patience:
<br>But then a noise did scare me from the tomb;
<br>And she, too desperate, would not go with me,
<br>But, as it seems, did violence on herself.
<br>All this I know; and to the marriage
<span class='playlinenum'>3240</span><br>Her nurse is privy: and, if aught in this
<br>Miscarried by my fault, let my old life
<br>Be sacrificed, some hour before his time,
<br>Unto the rigour of severest law.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Prince Escalus. </strong><a name='3245'></a>We still have known thee for a holy man.
<span class='playlinenum'>3245</span><br>Where's Romeo's man? what can he say in this?
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Balthasar. </strong><a name='3247'></a>I brought my master news of Juliet's death;
<br>And then in post he came from Mantua
<br>To this same place, to this same monument.
<br>This letter he early bid me give his father,
<span class='playlinenum'>3250</span><br>And threatened me with death, going in the vault,
<br>I departed not and left him there.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Prince Escalus. </strong><a name='3253'></a>Give me the letter; I will look on it.
<br>Where is the county's page, that raised the watch?
<br>Sirrah, what made your master in this place?
<span class='playlinenum'>3255</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Page. </strong><a name='3256'></a>He came with flowers to strew his lady's grave;
<br>And bid me stand aloof, and so I did:
<br>Anon comes one with light to ope the tomb;
<br>And by and by my master drew on him;
<br>And then I ran away to call the watch.
<span class='playlinenum'>3260</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Prince Escalus. </strong><a name='3261'></a>This letter doth make good the friar's words,
<br>Their course of love, the tidings of her death:
<br>And here he writes that he did buy a poison
<br>Of a poor 'pothecary, and therewithal
<br>Came to this vault to die, and lie with Juliet.
<span class='playlinenum'>3265</span><br>Where be these enemies? Capulet! Montague!
<br>See, what a scourge is laid upon your hate,
<br>That heaven finds means to kill your joys with love.
<br>And I for winking at your discords too
<br>Have lost a brace of kinsmen: all are punish'd.
<span class='playlinenum'>3270</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Capulet. </strong><a name='3271'></a>O brother Montague, give me thy hand:
<br>This is my daughter's jointure, for no more
<br>Can I demand.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Montague. </strong><a name='3274'></a>But I can give thee more:
<br>For I will raise her statue in pure gold;
<span class='playlinenum'>3275</span><br>That while Verona by that name is known,
<br>There shall no figure at such rate be set
<br>As that of true and faithful Juliet.
</li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Capulet. </strong><a name='3279'></a>As rich shall Romeo's by his lady's lie;
<br>Poor sacrifices of our enmity!
<span class='playlinenum'>3280</span></li></ul>

<ul><li class='playtext'><strong>Prince Escalus. </strong><a name='3281'></a>A glooming peace this morning with it brings;
<br>The sun, for sorrow, will not show his head:
<br>Go hence, to have more talk of these sad things;
<br>Some shall be pardon'd, and some punished:
<br>For never was a story of more woe
<span class='playlinenum'>3285</span><br>Than this of Juliet and her Romeo.
</li></ul>

</li></ul><p class='stagedir'><a name='3287'></a>[Exeunt]</li></ul>
